# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antenna-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] In electromagnetics and antenna theory, the **aperture** of an antenna is defined as "A surface, near or on an antenna, on which it is convenient to make assumptions regarding the field values for the purpose of computing fields at external points.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] The incoming radiation is assumed to have the same polarization as the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] The effective area of an antenna or aperture is based upon a *receiving* antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] However, due to reciprocity, an antenna's directivity in receiving and transmitting are identical, so the power transmitted by an antenna in different directions (the radiation pattern) is also proportional to the effective area $A_{e}$ .
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] When no direction is specified, $A_{e}$ is understood to refer to its maximal value.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Most antenna designs are not defined by a physical area but consist of wires or thin rods; then the effective aperture bears no clear relation to the size or area of the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] The longer the effective length, the greater is the voltage appearing at its terminals.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] However, the actual power implied by that voltage depends on the antenna's feedpoint impedance, so this cannot be directly related to antenna gain, which *is* a measure of received power (but does not directly specify voltage or current).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] For instance, a half-wave dipole has a much longer effective length than a short dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] However the effective area of the short dipole is almost as great as it is for the half-wave antenna, since (ideally), given an ideal impedance-matching network, it can receive almost as much power from that wave.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Note that for a given antenna feedpoint impedance, an antenna's gain or $A_{\text{eff}}$ increases according to the *square* of $l_{\text{eff}}$ , so that the effective length for an antenna relative to different wave directions follows the *square root* of the gain in those directions.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] But since changing the physical size of an antenna inevitably changes the impedance (often by a great factor), the effective length is not by itself a useful figure of merit for describing an antenna's peak directivity and is more of theoretical importance.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] In practice, the effective length of a particular antenna is often combined with its impedance and loss to become the realized effective length.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] In general, the aperture of an antenna cannot be directly inferred from its physical size.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] That power removed from the plane wave can be actually received by the antenna (converted into electrical power), reflected or otherwise scattered, or absorbed (converted to heat).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] In this case the *effective aperture* $A_{e}$ is always less than (or equal to) the area of the antenna's physical aperture $A_{\text{phys}}$ , as it accounts only for the portion of that wave actually received as electrical power.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] The **aperture efficiency** is a dimensionless parameter between 0 and 1 that measures how close the antenna comes to using all the radio wave power intersecting its physical aperture.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] If the aperture efficiency were 100%, then all the wave's power falling on its physical aperture would be converted to electrical power delivered to the load attached to its output terminals, so these two areas would be equal: $A_{\text{e}}=A_{\text{phys}}$ .
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] But due to nonuniform illumination by a parabolic dish's feed, as well as other scattering or loss mechanisms, this is not achieved in practice.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Since a parabolic antenna's cost and wind load increase with the *physical* aperture size, there may be a strong motivation to reduce these (while achieving a specified antenna gain) by maximizing the aperture efficiency.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Aperture efficiencies of typical aperture antennas vary from 0.35 to well over 0.70.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Note that when one simply speaks of an antenna's "efficiency", what is most often meant is the *radiation efficiency*, a measure which applies to all antennas (not just aperture antennas) and accounts only for the gain reduction due to losses.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Outside of aperture antennas, most antennas consist of thin wires or rods with a small physical cross-sectional area (generally much smaller than $A_{\text{e}}$ ) for which "aperture efficiency" is not even defined.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] The *directivity* of an antenna, its ability to direct radio waves preferentially in one direction or receive preferentially from a given direction, is expressed by a parameter G called *antenna gain*.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] This is most commonly defined as the ratio of the power $P_{\text{o}}$ received by that antenna from waves in a given direction to the power $P_{\text{iso}}$ that would be received by an ideal isotropic antenna, that is, a hypothetical antenna that receives power equally well from all directions.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] where $\lambda$ is the wavelength of the radio waves.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] So antennas with large effective apertures are considered high-gain antennas (or *beam antennas*), which have relatively small angular beam widths.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] As receiving antennas, they are much more sensitive to radio waves coming from a preferred direction compared to waves coming from other directions (which would be considered interference).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] As transmitting antennas, most of their power is radiated in a particular direction at the expense of other directions.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Although antenna gain and effective aperture are functions of direction, when no direction is specified, these are understood to refer to their maximal values, that is, in the direction(s) of the antenna's intended use (also referred to as the antenna's main lobe or boresight).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] The fraction of the power delivered to a transmitting antenna that is received by a receiving antenna is proportional to the product of the apertures of both the antennas and inversely proportional to the squared values of the distance between the antennas and the wavelength.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] is the wavelength of the radio frequency.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] The aperture of an isotropic antenna, the basis of the definition of gain above, can be derived on the basis of consistency with thermodynamics.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Suppose that an ideal isotropic antenna *A* with a driving-point impedance of *R* sits within a closed system CA in thermodynamic equilibrium at temperature *T*.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] We connect the antenna terminals to a resistor also of resistance *R* inside a second closed system CR, also at temperature *T*.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] In between may be inserted an arbitrary lossless electronic filter *Fν* passing only some frequency components.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Each cavity is in thermal equilibrium and thus filled with black-body radiation due to temperature *T*.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] The mean-squared voltage ${\overline {v_{n}^{2}}}={\text{v}}_{\text{rms}}^{2}$ can be found by integrating the above equation for the spectral density of mean-squared noise voltage over frequencies passed by the filter *Fν*.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] This power due to Johnson noise from the resistor is received by the antenna, which radiates it into the closed system CA.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] using the notation $\eta (f)$ defined above.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] However, that radiation is unpolarized, whereas the antenna is only sensitive to one polarization, reducing it by a factor of 2.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Since we have assumed an isotropic radiator, *A*eff is independent of angle, so the integration over solid angles is trivial, introducing a factor of 4π.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] And again we can take the simple case of a narrowband electronic filter function *Fν* which only passes power of bandwidth *B*1 around frequency *f*1.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] where $\lambda _{1}=c/f_{1}$ is the free-space wavelength corresponding to the frequency *f*1.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Since each system is in thermodynamic equilibrium at the same temperature, we expect no net transfer of power between the cavities.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Otherwise one cavity would heat up and the other would cool down in violation of the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] We thus find that for a hypothetical isotropic antenna, thermodynamics demands that the effective cross-section of the receiving antenna to have an area of λ2/4π.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] This result could be further generalized if we allow the integral over frequency to be more general.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Then we find that *A*eff for the same antenna must vary with frequency according to that same formula, using λ = *c*/*f*.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Moreover, the integral over solid angle can be generalized for an antenna that is *not* isotropic (that is, any real antenna).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Although the above is sufficient proof, we can note that the condition of the antenna's impedance being *R*, the same as the resistor, can also be relaxed.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] In principle, any antenna impedance (that isn't totally reactive) can be impedance-matched to the resistor *R* by inserting a suitable (lossless) matching network.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Since that network is lossless, the powers *P*A and *P*R will still flow in opposite directions, even though the voltage and currents seen at the antenna and resistor's terminals will differ.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] The spectral density of the power flow in either direction will still be given by $k_{\text{B}}T\,\eta (f)$ , and in fact this is the very thermal-noise power spectral density associated with one electromagnetic mode, be it in free-space or transmitted electrically.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] Since there is only a single connection to the resistor, the resistor itself represents a single mode.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-aperture] And an antenna, also having a single electrical connection, couples to one mode of the electromagnetic field according to its average effective cross-section of $\lambda _{1}^{2}/(4\pi )$ .
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] In electromagnetics, an antenna's **gain** is a key performance parameter which combines the antenna's directivity and radiation efficiency.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] The term *power gain* has been deprecated by IEEE.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] In a transmitting antenna, the gain describes how well the antenna converts input power into radio waves headed in a specified direction.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] In a receiving antenna, the gain describes how well the antenna converts radio waves arriving from a specified direction into electrical power.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] When no direction is specified, gain is understood to refer to the peak value of the gain, the gain in the direction of the antenna's main lobe.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] A plot of the gain as a function of direction is called the antenna pattern or radiation pattern.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] It is not to be confused with directivity, which does *not* take an antenna's radiation efficiency into account.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] Gain or 'absolute gain' is defined as "The ratio of the radiation intensity in a given direction to the radiation intensity that would be produced if the power accepted by the antenna were isotropically radiated".
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] Usually this ratio is expressed in decibels with respect to an isotropic radiator (dBi).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] An alternative definition compares the received power to the power received by a lossless half-wave dipole antenna, in which case the units are written as "dBd".
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] Since a lossless dipole antenna has a gain of 2.15 dBi, the relation between these units is Gain(dBd) ≈ Gain(dBi) − 2.15.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] For a given frequency, the antenna's effective area is proportional to the gain.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] An antenna's effective length is proportional to the *square root* of the antenna's gain for a particular frequency and radiation resistance.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] Due to reciprocity, the gain of any antenna when receiving is equal to its gain when transmitting.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] A transmitting antenna is supplied with power by a transmission line connecting the antenna to a radio transmitter.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] The **power accepted by the antenna** $P_{\mathrm {O} }$ is the power supplied to the antenna's terminals.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] Losses prior to the antenna terminals are accounted for by separate impedance mismatch factors which are therefore not included in the calculation of radiation efficiency.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] Published numbers for antenna gain are almost always expressed in decibels (dB), a logarithmic scale.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] Therefore, an antenna with a peak power gain of 5 would be said to have a gain of 7 dBi.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] 'dBi' is used rather than just 'dB' to emphasize that this is the gain according to the basic definition, in which the antenna is compared to an isotropic radiator.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] When actual measurements of an antenna's gain are made by a laboratory, the field strength of the test antenna is measured when supplied with, say, 1 watt of transmitter power, at a certain distance.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] That field strength is compared to the field strength found using a so-called *reference antenna* at the same distance receiving the same power in order to determine the gain of the antenna under test.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] That ratio would be equal to ⁠ G ⁠ if the reference antenna were an isotropic radiator ("irad").
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] However a true isotropic radiator cannot be built, so in practice a different antenna is used.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] This will often be a half-wave dipole, a very well understood and repeatable antenna that can be easily built for any frequency.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] The directive gain of a half-wave dipole with respect to the isotropic radiator is known to be 1.64 and it can be made nearly 100% efficient.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] Since the gain has been measured with respect to this reference antenna, the difference in the gain of the test antenna is often compared to that of the dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] The gain relative to a dipole is thus often quoted and is denoted using 'dBd' instead of 'dBi' to avoid confusion.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] For instance, the above antenna with a gain ⁠ G ⁠ = 5 would have a gain with respect to a dipole of 5/1.64 ≈ 3.05, or in decibels one would call this 10 log(3.05) ≈ 4.84 dBd.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] When an antenna's maximum gain is specified in decibels (for instance, by a manufacturer) one must be certain as to whether this means the gain relative to an isotropic radiator or with respect to a dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] If it specifies dBi or dBd then there is no ambiguity, but if only dB is specified then the fine print must be consulted.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] Either figure can be easily converted into the other using the above relationship.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] When considering an antenna's directional pattern, gain with respect to a dipole does *not* imply a comparison of that antenna's gain in each direction to a dipole's gain in that direction.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] Rather, it is a comparison between the antenna's gain in each direction to the *peak* gain of the dipole (1.64).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] In any direction, therefore, such numbers are 2.15 dB smaller than the gain expressed in dBi.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] where $U_{\theta }$ and $U_{\phi }$ represent the radiation intensity in a given direction contained in their respective E field component.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] Let us find the gain of such an antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] Since the antenna is specified as being lossless the radiation efficiency is 1.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] As an example, consider an antenna that radiates an electromagnetic wave whose electrical field has an amplitude $E_{\theta }$ at a distance ⁠ r ⁠.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] The radiated wave can be considered locally as a plane wave.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] If the resistive part of the series impedance of the antenna is ⁠ ${R_{s}}$ ⁠, the power fed to the antenna is ⁠ $\textstyle {1 \over 2}{R_{s}I^{2}}$ ⁠.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] Sometimes, the half-wave dipole is taken as a reference instead of the isotropic radiator.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] When testing mobile devices, TRP can be measured while in close proximity of power-absorbing losses such as the body and hand of the user.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] The TRP can be used to determine body loss (BoL).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-gain] The body loss is considered as the ratio of TRP measured in the presence of losses and TRP measured while in free space.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In radio-frequency engineering, an **antenna** (American English) or **aerial** (British English) is a structure used to convert alternating electric currents into radio waves for transmission, and to convert radio waves back into electric currents for reception.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] It is the interface between radio waves propagating through space and electric currents moving in metal conductors, used with a transmitter or receiver.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In transmission, a radio transmitter supplies an electric current to the antenna's terminals, and the antenna radiates the energy from the current as electromagnetic waves (radio waves).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In reception, an antenna intercepts some of the power of a radio wave in order to produce an electric current at its terminals, that is applied to a receiver to be amplified.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas are essential components of all radio equipment.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna is an array of conductor segments (elements), electrically connected to the receiver or transmitter.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas can be designed to transmit and receive radio waves in all horizontal directions equally (omnidirectional antennas), or preferentially in a particular direction (directional, or high-gain, or "beam" antennas).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna may include components not connected to the transmitter, parabolic reflectors, horns, or parasitic elements, which serve to direct the radio waves into a beam or other desired radiation pattern.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Strong directivity and good transmitting efficiency when transmitting are hard to achieve with antennas whose dimensions are much smaller than a half wavelength.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The first antennas were built in 1886 by German physicist Heinrich Hertz in his pioneering experiments to prove the existence of electromagnetic waves predicted by the 1867 electromagnetic theory of James Clerk Maxwell.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Hertz placed dipole antennas at the focal point of parabolic reflectors for both transmitting and receiving.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Starting in 1895, Guglielmo Marconi began development of antennas practical for long-distance wireless telegraphy and opened a factory in Chelmsford, England, to manufacture his invention in 1898.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] antenna receiving a radio wave: The electric field (E) of the wave excites oscillating currents (black arrows) in the receiver.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna radiating radio waves: The transmitter applies an alternating current (red arrows) to the rods, which charges them alternately positive and negative, emitting loops of electric field.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The arrows of the loops get reversed each time the current changes polarity.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The words *antenna* and *aerial* are used interchangeably.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Occasionally the equivalent term "aerial" is used to specifically mean an elevated horizontal wire antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The origin of the word *antenna* relative to wireless apparatus is attributed to Italian radio pioneer Guglielmo Marconi.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In the summer of 1895, Marconi began testing his wireless system outdoors on his father's estate near Bologna and soon began to experiment with long wire "aerials" suspended from a pole.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In Italian a tent pole is known as *l'antenna centrale*, and the pole with the wire was simply called *l'antenna*.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Until then wireless radiating transmitting and receiving elements were known simply as "terminals".
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Because of his prominence, Marconi's use of the word *antenna* spread among wireless researchers and enthusiasts, and later to the general public.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas are required by any radio receiver or transmitter to couple its electrical connection to the electromagnetic field.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Radio waves are electromagnetic waves that carry signals through space at the speed of light; in free space they propagate without material absorption, apart from geometric spreading loss.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas can be classified as omnidirectional, radiating energy approximately equally in all horizontal directions, or directional, where radio waves are concentrated in some direction(s).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] A so-called beam antenna is *unidirectional* – designed for maximum response in the direction of the remote station they are aligned with – whereas many other antennas are intended to respond to stations in several directions, but are not truly omnidirectional.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Since antennas obey *reciprocity*, the same radiation pattern applies both to transmission as well as reception of radio waves.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] A hypothetical antenna that radiates equally in all directions (vertical as well as all horizontal angles) is called an *isotropic radiator*; however, *exact* uniformity cannot be accomplished in practical antennas, and is only rarely desired (e.g. emergency antennas for spacecraft).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Rather, for most terrestrial communications, there is an advantage in *reducing* radiation toward the sky or ground in favor of horizontal direction(s).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Several dipole elements of slightly different lengths can be stacked in parallel, into an antenna array such as the Yagi–Uda in order to focus their radiation into a single horizontal direction, perpendicular to the stack, thus termed a *beam antenna*.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] A half‑wave dipole antenna is a balanced element, with equal and opposite voltages and currents at its two terminals, and serves as a simple reference for analyzing many other antenna designs.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The vertical antenna is a *monopole* antenna, not balanced with respect to ground.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The ground (or any large conductive surface) plays the role of the second conductor of a monopole.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Since monopole antennas rely on a conductive surface, they may be mounted with a *ground plane* to approximate the effect of being mounted on the Earth's surface.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] More complex antennas increase the directivity of the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Additional elements in the antenna structure, which need not be directly connected to the receiver or transmitter, increase its directionality.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna "gain" describes the concentration of radiated power into a particular solid angle of space.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Unlike amplifier gain, which generally implies a net increase in signal power, antenna gain reflects a redistribution of power so that more is radiated in some directions and less in others, without increasing the total radiated power.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Unlike amplifiers, antennas are electrically "passive" devices which conserve total power, and there is no increase in total power above that delivered from the power source (the transmitter), only improved distribution of that fixed total.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] A phased array consists of two or more simple antennas which are connected together through an electrical network.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This often involves a number of parallel dipole antennas with a certain spacing.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Depending on the relative phase introduced by the network, the same combination of dipole antennas can operate as a "broadside array" (directional normal to a line connecting the elements) or as an "end-fire array" (directional along the line connecting the elements).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna arrays may employ any basic (omnidirectional or weakly directional) antenna type, such as dipole, loop or slot antennas.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Log‑periodic and other frequency‑independent antennas employ self‑similar structures in order to operate effectively over a wide range of frequencies (i.e., with wide bandwidth).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The most familiar example is the log-periodic dipole array which can be seen as a number (typically 10 to 20) of connected dipole elements with progressive lengths in an endfire array making it rather directional; it finds use especially as a rooftop antenna for television reception.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, a Yagi–Uda antenna (or simply "Yagi"), with a somewhat similar appearance, has only one dipole element with an electrical connection; the other parasitic elements interact with the electromagnetic field in order to realize a highly directional antenna but with a narrow bandwidth.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Even greater directionality can be obtained using *aperture antennas* such as the parabolic reflector or horn antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Since high directivity in an antenna depends on it being large compared to the wavelength, highly directional antennas (thus with high antenna gain) become more practical at higher frequencies (UHF and above).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] At low frequencies (such as AM broadcast), arrays of vertical towers are used to achieve directionality and they will occupy large areas of land.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] For reception, a long Beverage antenna can have significant directivity.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] For non directional portable use, a short vertical antenna or small loop antenna works well, with the main design challenge being that of impedance matching.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] With a vertical antenna a *loading coil* at the base of the antenna may be employed to cancel the reactive component of impedance; small loop antennas are tuned with parallel capacitors for this purpose.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna *lead-in* is the transmission line, or feed line, that connects the antenna to a transmitter or receiver.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The "antenna feed" may refer to all components connecting the antenna to the transmitter or receiver, such as an impedance matching network in addition to the transmission line.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] A microwave antenna may also be fed directly from a waveguide in place of a (conductive) transmission line.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna counterpoise, or ground plane, is a structure of conductive material which improves or substitutes for the ground.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] It may be connected to or insulated from the natural ground.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In a monopole antenna, this aids in the function of the natural ground, particularly where variations (or limitations) of the characteristics of the natural ground interfere with its proper function.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Such a structure is normally connected to the return connection of an unbalanced transmission line such as the shield of a coaxial cable.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] An electromagnetic wave refractor in some aperture antennas is a component which due to its shape and position functions to selectively delay or advance portions of the electromagnetic wavefront passing through it.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The refractor alters the spatial characteristics of the wave on one side relative to the other side.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] It can, for instance, bring the wave to a focus or alter the wave front in other ways, generally in order to maximize the directivity of the antenna system.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This is the radio equivalent of an optical lens.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna coupling network is a passive network (generally a combination of inductive and capacitive circuit elements) used for impedance matching in between the antenna and the transmitter or receiver.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This may be used to minimize losses on the feed line, by reducing transmission line's standing wave ratio, and to present the transmitter or receiver with a standard resistive impedance needed for its optimum operation.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The feed point location(s) is selected, and antenna elements electrically similar to tuner components may be incorporated in the antenna structure itself, to improve the match.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] It is a fundamental property of antennas that most of the electrical characteristics of an antenna, such as those described in the next section (e.g. gain, radiation pattern, impedance, bandwidth, resonant frequency and polarization), are the same whether the antenna is transmitting or receiving.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This equivalence follows reciprocity theorem of electromagnetics.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Therefore, in discussions of antenna properties no distinction is usually made between receiving and transmitting terminology, and the antenna can be viewed as either transmitting or receiving, whichever is more convenient.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] A necessary condition for the aforementioned reciprocity property is that the materials in the antenna and transmission medium are linear and reciprocal.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] *Reciprocal* (or *bilateral*) means that the material has the same response to an electric current or magnetic field in one direction, as it has to the field or current in the opposite direction.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Most materials used in antennas meet these conditions, but some microwave antennas use high-tech components such as isolators and circulators, made of nonreciprocal materials such as ferrite.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] These can be used to give the antenna a different behavior on receiving than it has on transmitting, which can be useful in applications like radar.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The majority of antenna designs are based on the *resonance* principle.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This relies on the behaviour of moving electrons, which reflect off surfaces where the dielectric constant changes, in a fashion similar to the way light reflects when optical properties change.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In these designs, the reflective surface is created by the end of a conductor, normally a thin metal wire or rod, which in the simplest case has a *feed point* at one end where it is connected to a transmission line.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The conductor, or *element*, is aligned with the electrical field of the desired signal, normally meaning it is perpendicular to the line from the antenna to the source (or receiver in the case of a broadcast antenna).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The radio signal's electric component induces a voltage in the conductor.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This causes an electrical current to begin flowing in the direction of the signal's instantaneous field.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] When the resulting current reaches the end of the conductor, it reflects, which is equivalent to a 180 degree change in phase.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] If the conductor is ⁠ 1 /4⁠ of a wavelength long, current from the feed point will undergo 90 degree phase change by the time it reaches the end of the conductor, reflect through 180 degrees, and then another 90 degrees as it travels back.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] That means it has undergone a total 360 degree phase change, returning it to the original signal.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The current in the element thus adds to the current being created from the source at that instant.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This process creates a standing wave in the conductor, with the maximum current at the feed.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The ordinary half-wave dipole is probably the most widely used antenna design.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This consists of two ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength elements arranged end-to-end, and lying along essentially the same axis (or *collinear*), each feeding one side of a two-conductor transmission wire.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The physical arrangement of the two elements places them 180 degrees out of phase, which means that at any given instant one of the elements is driving current into the transmission line while the other is pulling it out.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The monopole antenna is essentially one half of the half-wave dipole, a single ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength element with the other side connected to ground or an equivalent ground plane (or *counterpoise*).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Monopoles, which are one-half the size of a dipole, are common for long-wavelength radio signals where a dipole would be impractically large.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Another common design is the folded dipole which consists of two (or more) half-wave dipoles placed side by side and connected at their ends but only one of which is driven.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The standing wave forms with this desired pattern at the design operating frequency, fo, and antennas are normally designed to be this size.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] However, feeding that element with 3 fo (whose wavelength is ⁠ 1 /3⁠ that of fo) will also lead to a standing wave pattern.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Thus, an antenna element is *also* resonant when its length is ⁠ 3 /4⁠ of a wavelength.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This is true for all odd multiples of ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wavelength.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This allows some flexibility of design in terms of antenna lengths and feed points.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas used in such a fashion are known to be *harmonically operated*.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Resonant antennas usually use a linear conductor (or *element*), or pair of such elements, each of which is about a quarter of the wavelength in length (an odd multiple of quarter wavelengths will also be resonant).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas that are required to be small compared to the wavelength sacrifice efficiency and cannot be very directional.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Since wavelengths are so small at higher frequencies (UHF, microwaves) trading off performance to obtain a smaller physical size is usually not required.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The quarter-wave elements imitate a series-resonant electrical element due to the standing wave present along the conductor.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] At the resonant frequency, the standing wave has a current peak and voltage node (minimum) at the feed.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In electrical terms, this means that at that position, the element has minimum impedance magnitude, generating the maximum current for minimum voltage.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This is the ideal situation, because it produces the maximum output for the minimum input, producing the highest possible efficiency.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Contrary to an ideal (lossless) series-resonant circuit, a finite resistance remains (corresponding to the relatively small voltage at the feed-point) due to the antenna's resistance to radiating, as well as any conventional electrical losses from producing heat.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Recall that a current will reflect when there are changes in the electrical properties of the material.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This leads to the concept of impedance matching, the design of the overall system of antenna and transmission line so the impedance is as close as possible, thereby reducing these losses.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Impedance matching is accomplished by a circuit called an antenna tuner or impedance matching network between the transmitter and antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The impedance match between the feedline and antenna is measured by a parameter called the standing wave ratio (SWR) on the feedline.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Consider a half-wave dipole designed to work with signals with wavelength 1 m, meaning the antenna would be approximately 50 cm from tip to tip.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] If the element has a length-to-diameter ratio of 1000, it will have an inherent impedance of about 63 ohms resistive.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Using the appropriate transmission wire or balun, we match that resistance to ensure minimum signal reflection.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Feeding that antenna with a current of 1 Ampere will require 63 Volts, and the antenna will radiate 63 Watts (ignoring losses) of radio frequency power.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Now consider the case when the antenna is fed a signal with a wavelength of 1.25 m; in this case the current induced by the signal would arrive at the antenna's feedpoint out-of-phase with the signal, causing the net current to drop while the voltage remains the same.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Electrically this appears to be a very high impedance.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The antenna and transmission line no longer have the same impedance, and the signal will be reflected back into the antenna, reducing output.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This could be addressed by changing the matching system between the antenna and transmission line, but that solution only works well at the new design frequency.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The result is that the resonant antenna will efficiently feed a signal into the transmission line only when the source signal's frequency is close to that of the design frequency of the antenna, or one of the resonant multiples.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This makes resonant antenna designs inherently narrow-band: Only useful for a small range of frequencies centered around the resonance(s).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] It is possible to use simple impedance matching techniques to allow the use of monopole or dipole antennas substantially shorter than the ⁠ 1 /4⁠ or ⁠ 1 /2⁠ wave, respectively, at which they are resonant.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Sometimes the resulting (lower) electrical resonant frequency of such a system (antenna plus matching network) is described using the concept of *electrical length*.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] An antenna operated at a lower frequency than its self‑resonant frequency is then called an *electrically short antenna*.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] For example, at 30 MHz (10 m wavelength) a true resonant ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wave monopole would be almost 2.5 meters long, and using an antenna only 1.5 meters tall would require the addition of a loading coil.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Then it may be said that the coil has lengthened the antenna to achieve an electrical length of 2.5 meters.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] However, the resulting resistive impedance achieved will be quite a bit lower than that of a true ⁠ 1 /4⁠ wave (resonant) monopole, often requiring further impedance matching (a transformer) to the desired transmission line.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] For ever shorter antennas (requiring greater "electrical lengthening") the radiation resistance plummets (approximately according to the square of the antenna length), so that the mismatch due to a net reactance away from the electrical resonance worsens.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Or one could as well say that the equivalent resonant circuit of the antenna system has a higher Q factor and thus a reduced bandwidth, which can even become inadequate for the transmitted signal's spectrum.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Resistive losses due to the loading coil, relative to the decreased radiation resistance, entail a reduced electrical efficiency, which can be of great concern for a transmitting antenna, but bandwidth is the major factor that sets the size of antennas at 1 MHz and lower frequencies.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The power flux density of the field from a transmitting antenna decreases with distance according to the inverse-square law, reflecting the geometrical spreading of the wave.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] For a given incoming flux, the power captured by a receiving antenna is proportional to its *effective area*.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] A half‑wave dipole, for example, has an effective area of about 0.13 λ2 when viewed from broadside.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] For an already efficient antenna design, the effective area (and thus gain) in a given direction can be increased only by reducing the gain in other directions.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] If a half-wave dipole is not connected to an external circuit but rather shorted out at the feedpoint, then it becomes a resonant half-wave element which efficiently produces a standing wave in response to an impinging radio wave.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Because there is no load to absorb that power, it retransmits all of that power, possibly with a phase shift which is critically dependent on the element's exact length.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Thus such a conductor can be arranged in order to transmit a second copy of a transmitter's signal in order to affect the radiation pattern (and feedpoint impedance) of the element electrically connected to the transmitter.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna elements used in this way are known as passive radiators.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] A Yagi–Uda array uses passive elements to greatly increase gain in one direction (at the expense of other directions).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] A number of parallel approximately half-wave elements (of very specific lengths) are situated parallel to each other, at specific positions, along a boom; the boom is only for support and not involved electrically.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Only one of the elements is electrically connected to the transmitter or receiver, while the remaining elements are passive.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The Yagi produces a fairly large gain (depending on the number of passive elements) and is widely used as a directional antenna with an antenna rotor to control the direction of its beam.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] It suffers from having a rather limited bandwidth, restricting its use to certain applications.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] What's more, a phased array can be made "steerable", that is, by changing the phases applied to each element the radiation pattern can be shifted *without* physically moving the antenna elements.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] When a radio wave hits a large conducting sheet it is reflected (with the phase of the electric field reversed) just as a mirror reflects light.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Placing such a reflector behind an otherwise non-directional antenna will insure that the power that would have gone in its direction is redirected toward the desired direction, increasing the antenna's gain by a factor of at least 2.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Likewise, a corner reflector can insure that all of the antenna's power is concentrated in only one quadrant of space (or less) with a consequent increase in gain.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Practically speaking, the reflector need not be a solid metal sheet, but can consist of a curtain of rods aligned with the antenna's polarization; this greatly reduces the reflector's weight and wind load.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Specular reflection of radio waves is also employed in a parabolic reflector antenna, in which a *curved* reflecting surface effects focussing of an incoming wave toward a so-called feed antenna; this results in an antenna system with an effective area comparable to the size of the reflector itself.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Other concepts from geometrical optics are also employed in antenna technology, such as with the lens antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The antenna's power gain (or simply "gain") also takes into account the antenna's efficiency, and is often the primary figure of merit.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas are characterized by a number of performance measures which a user would be concerned with in selecting or designing an antenna for a particular application.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] A plot of the directional characteristics in the space surrounding the antenna is its *radiation pattern*.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The frequency range or *bandwidth* over which an antenna functions well can be very wide (as in a log-periodic antenna) or narrow (as in a small loop antenna); outside this range the antenna impedance becomes a poor match to the transmission line and transmitter (or receiver).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Use of the antenna well away from its design frequency affects its radiation pattern, reducing its directive gain.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Generally an antenna will not have a feed-point impedance that matches that of a transmission line; a matching network between antenna terminals and the transmission line will improve power transfer to the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] A non-adjustable matching network will most likely place further limits the usable bandwidth of the antenna system.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] It may be desirable to use tubular elements, instead of thin wires, to make an antenna; these will allow a greater bandwidth.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Or, several thin wires can be grouped in a *cage* to simulate a thicker element.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This widens the bandwidth of the resonance.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Amateur radio antennas that operate at several frequency bands which are widely separated from each other may connect elements resonant at those different frequencies in parallel.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Most of the transmitter's power will flow into the resonant element while the others present a high impedance.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Another solution uses *traps*, parallel resonant circuits which are strategically placed in breaks created in long antenna elements.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] When used at the trap's particular resonant frequency the trap presents a very high impedance (parallel resonance) effectively truncating the element at the location of the trap; if positioned correctly, the truncated element makes a proper resonant antenna at the trap frequency.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] At substantially higher or lower frequencies the trap allows the full length of the broken element to be employed, but with a resonant frequency shifted by the net reactance added by the trap.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The bandwidth characteristics of a resonant antenna element can be characterized according to its *Q* where the resistance involved is the radiation resistance, which represents the emission of energy from the resonant antenna to free space.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The *Q* of a narrow band antenna can be as high as 15.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, the reactance at the same off-resonant frequency of one using thick elements is much less, consequently resulting in a *Q* as low as 5.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] These two antennas may perform equivalently at the resonant frequency, but the second antenna will perform over a bandwidth 3 times as wide as the antenna consisting of a thin conductor.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antennas for use over much broader frequency ranges are achieved using further techniques.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Adjustment of a matching network can, in principle, allow for any antenna to be matched at any frequency.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Thus the small loop antenna built into most AM broadcast (medium wave) receivers has a very narrow bandwidth, but is tuned using a parallel capacitance which is adjusted according to the receiver tuning.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, log-periodic antennas are *not* resonant at any single frequency but can (in principle) be built to attain similar characteristics (including feedpoint impedance) over any frequency range.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] These are therefore commonly used (in the form of directional log-periodic dipole arrays) as television antennas.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Gain is a parameter which measures the degree of directivity of the antenna's radiation pattern.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] A high-gain antenna will radiate most of its power in a particular direction, while a low-gain antenna will radiate over a wide angle.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] High-gain antennas have the advantage of longer range and better signal quality, but must be aimed carefully at the other antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] An example of a high-gain antenna is a parabolic dish such as a satellite television antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Low-gain antennas have shorter range, but the orientation of the antenna is relatively unimportant.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] An example of a low-gain antenna is the whip antenna found on portable radios and cordless phones.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna gain should not be confused with amplifier gain, a separate parameter measuring the increase in signal power due to an amplifying device placed at the front-end of the system, such as a low-noise amplifier.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The *effective area* or effective aperture of a receiving antenna expresses the portion of the power of a passing electromagnetic wave which the antenna delivers to its terminals, expressed in terms of an equivalent area.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] For instance, if a radio wave passing a given location has a flux of 1 pW / m2 (10−12 Watts per square meter) and an antenna has an effective area of 12 m2, then the antenna would deliver 12 pW of RF power to the receiver (30 microvolts RMS at 75 ohms).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Since the receiving antenna is not equally sensitive to signals received from all directions, the effective area is a function of the direction to the source.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Due to reciprocity (discussed above) the gain of an antenna used for transmitting must be proportional to its effective area when used for receiving.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Consider an antenna with no loss, that is, one whose electrical efficiency is 100%.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] It can be shown that its effective area averaged over all directions must be equal to λ2/4π, the wavelength squared divided by 4π.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Gain is defined such that the average gain over all directions for an antenna with 100% electrical efficiency is equal to 1.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] For an antenna with an efficiency of less than 100%, both the effective area and gain are reduced by that same amount.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Therefore, the above relationship between gain and effective area still holds.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] These are thus two different ways of expressing the same quantity.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] *A*eff is especially convenient when computing the power that would be received by an antenna of a specified gain, as illustrated by the above example.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The radiation pattern of an antenna is a plot of the relative field strength of the radio waves emitted by the antenna at different angles in the far field.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] It is typically represented by a three-dimensional graph, or polar plots of the horizontal and vertical cross sections.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The pattern of an ideal isotropic antenna, which radiates equally in all directions, would look like a sphere.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Many nondirectional antennas, such as monopoles and dipoles, emit equal power in all horizontal directions, with the power dropping off at higher and lower angles; this is called an omnidirectional pattern and when plotted looks like a torus or donut.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The radiation of many antennas shows a pattern of maxima or "*lobes*" at various angles, separated by "*nulls*", angles where the radiation falls to zero.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] This is because the radio waves emitted by different parts of the antenna typically interfere, causing maxima at angles where the radio waves arrive at distant points in phase, and zero radiation at other angles where the radio waves arrive out of phase.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In a directional antenna designed to project radio waves in a particular direction, the lobe in that direction is designed larger than the others and is called the "*main lobe*".
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The other lobes usually represent unwanted radiation and are called "*sidelobes*".
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The axis through the main lobe is called the "*principal axis*" or "*boresight axis*".
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The polar radiation patterns of Yagi antennas become narrower, and their directivity (and thus gain) increases, when they are designed for a relatively narrow frequency range, as compared with wideband designs.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The space surrounding an antenna can be divided into three concentric regions: The reactive near-field (also called the inductive near-field), the radiating near-field (Fresnel region) and the far-field (Fraunhofer) regions.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] These regions are useful to identify the field structure in each, although the transitions between them are gradual; there are no clear boundaries.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The orientation and physical structure of an antenna determine the *polarization* of the electric field of the radio wave transmitted by it.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] For instance, an antenna composed of a linear conductor (such as a dipole or whip antenna) oriented vertically will result in vertical polarization; if turned on its side the same antenna's polarization will be horizontal.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In the most general case, polarization is elliptical, meaning that over each cycle the electric field vector traces out an ellipse.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Two special cases are linear polarization (the ellipse collapses into a line) as discussed above, and circular polarization (in which the two axes of the ellipse are equal).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In linear polarization the electric field of the radio wave oscillates along one direction.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In circular polarization, the electric field of the radio wave rotates around the axis of propagation.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Circular or elliptically polarized radio waves are designated as right-handed or left-handed using the "thumb in the direction of the propagation" rule.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Note that for circular polarization, optical researchers use the opposite right-hand rule from the one used by radio engineers.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] It is best for the receiving antenna to match the polarization of the transmitted wave for optimum reception.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Otherwise there will be a loss of signal strength: when a linearly polarized antenna receives linearly polarized radiation at a relative angle of θ, then there will be a power loss of cos2θ .
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] A circularly polarized antenna can be used to equally well match vertical or horizontal linear polarizations, suffering a 3 dB signal reduction.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] However it will be blind to a circularly polarized signal of the opposite orientation.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Maximum power transfer requires matching the impedance of an antenna system (as seen looking into the transmission line) to the complex conjugate of the impedance of the receiver or transmitter.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The intended impedance is normally resistive, but a transmitter (and some receivers) may have limited additional adjustments to cancel a certain amount of reactance, in order to "tweak" the match.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The match is sought to minimize the amplitude of standing waves (measured via the standing wave ratio; SWR) that a mismatch raises on the line, and the increase in transmission line losses it entails.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Antenna tuning, in the strict sense of modifying the antenna itself, generally refers only to cancellation of any reactance seen at the antenna terminals, leaving only a resistive impedance which might or might not be exactly the desired impedance (that of the available transmission line).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Although an antenna may be designed to have a purely resistive feedpoint impedance (such as a dipole 97% of a half wavelength long) at just one frequency, this will very likely not be exactly true at other frequencies that the antenna is eventually used for.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In most cases, in principle the physical length of the antenna can be "trimmed" to obtain a pure resistance, although this is rarely convenient.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, the addition of a contrary inductance or capacitance can be used to cancel a residual capacitive or inductive reactance, respectively, and may be more convenient than lowering and trimming or extending the antenna, then hoisting it back.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In addition to those reactance-neutralizing add-ons, antennas of any kind may include a transformer and / or transformer balun at their feedpoint, to change the resistive part of the impedance to more nearly match the feedline's characteristic impedance.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] An additional problem is matching the remaining resistive impedance to the characteristic impedance of the transmission line: A general impedance matching network (an "antenna tuner" or ATU) will have at least two adjustable elements to correct both components of impedance.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Any matching network will have both power losses and power restrictions when used for transmitting.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Commercial antennas are generally designed to approximately match standard 50 Ohm coaxial cables, at standard frequencies; the design expectation is that a matching network will be merely used to 'tweak' any residual mismatch.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] In some cases matching is done in a more extreme manner, not simply to cancel a small amount of residual reactance, but to resonate an antenna whose resonance frequency is quite different from the intended frequency of operation.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The physically large inductor at the base of the antenna has an inductive reactance which is the opposite of the capacitative reactance that the short vertical antenna has at the desired operating frequency.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] (usually, but not always, for receiving) at a relatively low frequency, where it appears almost as a pure inductor.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] to produce a better-matched feedpoint resistance.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The loop is resonated by a coupled tuning capacitor, which is configured to match the receiver's tuning, in order to keep the antenna resonant at the chosen receive frequency over the AM broadcast band.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Ground reflections is one of the common types of multipath.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The radiation pattern and even the driving point impedance of an antenna can be influenced by the dielectric constant and especially conductivity of nearby objects.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] For a terrestrial antenna, the ground is usually one such object of importance.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The antenna's height above the ground, as well as the electrical properties (permittivity and conductivity) of the ground, can then be important.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Also, in the particular case of a monopole antenna, the ground (or an artificial ground plane) serves as the return connection for the antenna current thus having an additional effect, particularly on the impedance seen by the feed line.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] When an electromagnetic wave strikes a plane surface such as the ground, part of the wave is transmitted into the ground and part of it is reflected, according to the Fresnel coefficients.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] If the ground is a very good conductor then almost all of the wave is reflected (180° out of phase), whereas a ground modeled as a (lossy) dielectric can absorb a large amount of the wave's power.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The power remaining in the reflected wave, and the phase shift upon reflection, strongly depend on the wave's angle of incidence and polarization.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The dielectric constant and conductivity (or simply the complex dielectric constant) is dependent on the soil type and is a function of frequency.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] At lower mediumwave frequencies the ground acts mainly as a good conductor, which AM broadcast (0.5–1.7 MHz) antennas depend on.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] At frequencies between 3–30 MHz, a large portion of the energy from a horizontally polarized antenna reflects off the ground, with almost total reflection at the grazing angles important for ground wave propagation.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] That reflected wave, with its phase reversed, can either cancel or reinforce the direct wave, depending on the antenna height in wavelengths and elevation angle (for a sky wave).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] On the other hand, vertically polarized radiation is not well reflected by the ground except at grazing incidence or over very highly conducting surfaces such as sea water.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] However the grazing angle reflection important for ground wave propagation, using vertical polarization, is *in phase* with the direct wave, providing a boost of up to 6 dB, as is detailed below.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] At VHF and above (> 30 MHz) the ground becomes a poorer reflector.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] However, for shortwave frequencies, especially below ~15 MHz, it remains a good reflector especially for horizontal polarization and grazing angles of incidence.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] That is important as these higher frequencies usually depend on horizontal line-of-sight propagation (except for satellite communications), the ground then behaving almost as a mirror.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] The net quality of a ground reflection depends on the topography of the surface.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] When the irregularities of the surface are much smaller than the wavelength, the dominant regime is that of specular reflection, and the receiver sees both the real antenna and an image of the antenna under the ground due to reflection.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] But if the ground has irregularities not small compared to the wavelength, reflections will not be coherent but shifted by random phases.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] With shorter wavelengths (higher frequencies), this is generally the case.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] Whenever both the receiving or transmitting antenna are placed at significant heights above the ground (relative to the wavelength), waves reflected specularly by the ground will travel a longer distance than direct waves, inducing a phase shift which can sometimes be significant.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p01] When a sky wave is launched by such an antenna, that phase shift is always significant unless the antenna is very close to the ground (compared to the wavelength).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] The flow of current in wire antennas is identical to the solution of counter-propagating waves in a single conductor transmission line, which can be solved using the telegrapher's equations.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Unlike transmission lines, currents in antennas contribute power to the radiated part electromagnetic field, which can be modeled using radiation resistance.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] The combination of the incident and reflected wave, just as in a transmission line, forms a standing wave with a current node at the conductor's end, and a voltage node one-quarter wavelength from the end (if the element is at least that long).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] In a *resonant antenna*, the feedpoint of the antenna is at one of those voltage nodes.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Due to discrepancies from the simplified version of the transmission line model, the voltage one quarter wavelength from the current node is not exactly zero, but it is near a minimum, and small compared to the much larger voltage at the conductor's end.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Hence, a feed point matching the antenna at that spot requires a relatively small voltage but large current (the currents from the two waves add in-phase there), thus a relatively low feedpoint impedance.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Feeding the antenna at other points involves a large voltage, thus a large impedance, and usually one that is primarily reactive (low power factor), which is a terrible impedance match to available transmission lines.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Therefore, it is usually desired for an antenna to operate as a resonant element with each conductor having a length of one quarter wavelength (or any other odd multiples of a quarter wavelength).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] For instance, a half-wave dipole has two such elements (one connected to each conductor of a balanced transmission line) about one quarter wavelength long.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Depending on the conductors' diameters, a small deviation from this length is adopted in order to reach the point where the antenna current and the (small) feedpoint voltage are exactly in phase.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Then the antenna presents a purely resistive impedance, and ideally one close to the characteristic impedance of an available transmission line.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Despite these useful properties, resonant antennas have the disadvantage that they achieve resonance (purely resistive feedpoint impedance) only at a fundamental frequency, and perhaps some of its harmonics, and the feedpoint resistance is larger at higher-order resonances.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Therefore, resonant antennas can only achieve their good performance within a limited bandwidth, depending on the Q at the resonance.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] The electric and magnetic fields emanating from a driven antenna element will generally affect the voltages and currents in nearby antennas, antenna elements, or other conductors.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] This is particularly true when the affected conductor is a resonant element (multiple of half-wavelengths in length) at about the same frequency, as is the case where the conductors are all part of the same active or passive antenna array.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Thus using the mutual impedances calculated for a specific geometry, one can solve for the radiation pattern of a Yagi–Uda antenna or the currents and voltages for each element of a phased array.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Such an analysis can also describe in detail reflection of radio waves by a ground plane or by a corner reflector and their effect on the impedance (and radiation pattern) of an antenna in its vicinity.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Often such near-field interactions are undesired and pernicious.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Currents in random metal objects near a transmitting antenna will often be in poor conductors, causing loss of RF power in addition to unpredictably altering the characteristics of the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] By careful design, it is possible to reduce the electrical interaction between nearby conductors.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] For instance, the 90 degree angle in between the two dipoles composing the turnstile antenna ensures no interaction between these, allowing these to be driven independently (but actually with the same signal in quadrature phases in the turnstile antenna design).
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Antennas can be classified by operating principles or by their application.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] Different authorities placed antennas in narrower or broader categories.
[src:antenna-theory/antenna-radio-p02] These antenna types and others are summarized in greater detail in the overview article, Antenna types, as well as in each of the linked articles in the list above, and in even more detail in articles which those link to.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] In radio and telecommunications, a **dipole antenna** or **doublet** is one of the two simplest and most widely used types of antenna; the other is the monopole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The dipole is any one of a class of antennas producing a radiation pattern approximating that of an elementary electric dipole with a radiating structure supporting a line current so energized that the current has only one node at each far end.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A dipole antenna commonly consists of two identical conductive elements such as metal wires or rods.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The driving current from the transmitter is applied, or for receiving antennas the output signal to the receiver is taken, between the two halves of the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Each side of the feedline to the transmitter or receiver is connected to one of the conductors.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] This contrasts with a monopole antenna, which consists of a single rod or conductor with one side of the feedline connected to it, and the other side connected to some type of ground.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A common example of a dipole is the **rabbit ears** television antenna found on broadcast television sets.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] All dipoles are electrically equivalent to two monopoles mounted end-to-end and fed with opposite phases, with the ground plane between them made *virtual* by the opposing monopole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The dipole is the simplest type of antenna from a theoretical point of view.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Most commonly it consists of two conductors of equal length oriented end-to-end with the feedline connected between them.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Dipoles are frequently used as resonant antennas.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] If the feedpoint of such an antenna is shorted, then it will be able to resonate at a particular frequency, just like a guitar string that is plucked.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Using the antenna at around that frequency is advantageous in terms of feedpoint impedance (and thus standing wave ratio), so its length is determined by the intended wavelength (or frequency) of operation.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The most commonly used is the center-fed **half-wave dipole** which is just under a half-wavelength long.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The radiation pattern of the half-wave dipole is maximum perpendicular to the conductor, falling to zero in the axial direction, thus implementing an omnidirectional antenna if installed vertically, or (more commonly) a weakly directional antenna if horizontal.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Although they may be used as standalone low-gain antennas, dipoles are also employed as driven elements in more complex antenna designs such as the Yagi antenna and driven arrays.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Dipole antennas (or such designs derived from them, including the monopole) are used to feed more elaborate directional antennas such as a horn antenna, parabolic reflector, or corner reflector.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Engineers analyze vertical (or other monopole) antennas on the basis of dipole antennas of which they are one half.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] German physicist Heinrich Hertz first demonstrated the existence of radio waves in 1887 using what we now know as a dipole antenna (with capacitative end-loading).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] On the other hand, Guglielmo Marconi empirically found that he could just ground the transmitter (or one side of a transmission line, if used) dispensing with one half of the antenna, thus realizing the *vertical* or monopole antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] In the early days of radio, the thus-named Marconi antenna (monopole) and the doublet (dipole) were seen as distinct inventions.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Now, however, the monopole antenna is understood as a special case of a dipole which has a virtual element underground.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A short dipole is a dipole formed by two conductors with a total length ℓ substantially less than a half wavelength ( ⁠1/ 2 ⁠ λ ).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Short dipoles are sometimes used in applications where a full half-wave dipole would be too large.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] They can be analyzed easily using the results obtained below for the Hertzian dipole, a fictitious entity.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Being shorter than a resonant antenna (half a wavelength long) its feedpoint impedance includes a large capacitive reactance requiring a loading coil or other matching network in order to be practical, especially as a transmitting antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The feedpoint is usually at the center of the dipole as shown in the diagram.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The current along dipole arms are approximately described as proportional to $\ \sin(\ k\ z\ )\$ where z is the distance to the nearest end of the arm.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] In the case of a short dipole, that is essentially a linear drop from $\ I_{\mathrm {o} }\$ at the feedpoint to zero at the end.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] We have now expressed the flux in terms of the feedpoint current Io and the ratio of the short dipole's length ℓ to the wavelength of radiation λ.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The radiation pattern given by $\ \sin ^{2}\!(\ \theta \ )\$ is seen to be similar to and only slightly less directional than that of the half-wave dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Using the above expression for the radiation in the far field for a given feedpoint current, we can integrate over all solid angle to obtain the total radiated power.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] From that, it is possible to infer the radiation resistance, equal to the resistive (real) part of the feedpoint impedance, neglecting a component due to ohmic losses (presumed smaller).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Again, these approximations become quite accurate for ℓ ≪ ⁠1/ 2 ⁠λ .
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Setting *ℓ* = ⁠1/ 2 ⁠*λ* despite its use not quite being valid for so large a fraction of the wavelength, the formula would predict a radiation resistance of 49 Ω, instead of the actual value of 73 Ω produced by a half-wave dipole, when more correct quarter-wave sinusoidal currents are used.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The fundamental resonance of a thin linear conductor occurs at a frequency whose free-space wavelength is *twice* the wire's length; i.e. where the conductor is ⁠1/2⁠ wavelength long.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Dipole antennas are frequently used at around that frequency and thus termed *half-wave dipole* antennas.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] This important case is dealt with in the next section.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] where n is an integer, $\ \lambda ={\frac {\ c\ }{f}}\$ is the wavelength, and c is the reduced speed of radio waves in the radiating conductor (c ≈ 97%×co, the speed of light).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] For a center-fed dipole, however, there is a great dissimilarity between n being odd or being even.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Dipoles which are an *odd* number of half-wavelengths in length have reasonably low driving point impedances (which are purely resistive at that resonant frequency).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] However ones which are an *even* number of half-wavelengths in length, that is, an integer number of wavelengths in length, have a *high* driving point impedance (albeit purely resistive at that resonant frequency).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] For instance, a full-wave dipole antenna can be made with two half-wavelength conductors placed end to end for a total length of approximately $\ \ell \approx \lambda \ .$ This results in an additional gain over a half-wave dipole of about 2 dB.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Full wave dipoles can be used in short wave broadcasting only by making the effective diameter very large and feeding from a high impedance balanced line.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Cage dipoles are often used to get the large diameter.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A ⁠5/4⁠-wave dipole antenna has a much lower but not purely resistive feedpoint impedance, which requires a matching network to the impedance of the transmission line.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Its gain is about 3 dB greater than a half-wave dipole, the highest gain of any dipole of any similar length.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Other reasonable lengths of dipole do not offer advantages and are seldom used.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] However the overtone resonances of a half-wave dipole antenna at odd multiples of its fundamental frequency are sometimes exploited.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] For instance, amateur radio antennas designed as half-wave dipoles at 7 MHz can also be used as ⁠3/2⁠-wave dipoles at 21 MHz; likewise VHF television antennas resonant at the low VHF television band (centered around 65 MHz) are also resonant at the high VHF television band (around 195 MHz).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A half-wave dipole antenna consists of two quarter-wavelength conductors placed end to end for a total length of approximately ℓ = ⁠1/2⁠ *λ* .
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The directional factor ${\textstyle \ {\frac {\cos \left[\ {\tfrac {\pi }{2}}\ \cos \theta \ \right]}{\sin \theta }}\ }$ is very nearly the same as sin *θ* applying to the short dipole, resulting in a very similar radiation pattern as noted above.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Dividing Ptotal by ${\textstyle 4\pi r^{2}}$ supplies the flux at a large distance, *averaged* over all directions.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Dividing the flux in the *θ* = π/2 direction (where it is at its peak) at that large distance by the average flux, we find the directive gain to be 1.64 .
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] for the relationship between these functions.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] If a half-wave dipole is driven at a point other the center, then the feed point resistance will be higher.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The radiation resistance is *usually* expressed relative to the maximum current present along an antenna element, which for the half-wave dipole (and most other antennas) is also the current at the feedpoint.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] However, if the dipole is fed at a different point at a distance x from a current maximum (the center in the case of a half-wave dipole), then the current there is not I0 but only *I*0 cos( *k x* ) .
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] In order to supply the same power, the voltage at the feedpoint has to be similarly *increased* by the factor sec( *k x* ) .
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] This equation can also be used for dipole antennas of any length, provided that Rradiation has been computed relative to the current maximum, which is *not* generally the same as the feedpoint current for dipoles longer than half-wave.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Note that this equation breaks down when feeding an antenna near a current node, where cos( *k x* ) approaches zero.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The driving point impedance does indeed rise greatly, but is nevertheless limited due to higher order components of the elements' not-quite-exactly-sinusoidal current, which have been ignored above in the model for the current distribution.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A folded dipole is a half-wave dipole with an additional parallel wire connecting its two ends.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] If the additional wire has the same diameter and cross-section as the dipole, two nearly identical radiating currents are generated.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The resulting far-field emission pattern is nearly identical to the one for the single-wire dipole described above, but at resonance its feedpoint impedance $\ R_{\mathsf {f.d.}}\$ is four times the feedpoint impedance of a single-wire dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A folded dipole is, technically, a folded full-wave loop antenna, where the loop has been bent at opposing ends and squashed into two parallel wires in a flat line.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Although the broad bandwidth, high feedpoint impedance, and high efficiency are characteristics more similar to a full loop antenna, the folded dipole's radiation pattern is more like an ordinary dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Since the operation of a single halfwave dipole is easier to understand, both full loops and folded dipoles are often described as two halfwave dipoles in parallel, connected at the ends.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The high feedpoint impedance $\ R_{\mathsf {f.d.}}\$ at resonance is because for a fixed amount of power, the total radiating current $\ I_{0}\$ is equal to twice the current in each wire separately and thus equal to twice the current at the feed point.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] where $\ R_{\mathsf {h.w.}}\$ is the lower feedpoint impedance of the resonant halfwave dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Half-wave folded dipoles are often used for FM radio antennas; versions made with twin lead which can be hung on an inside wall often come with FM tuners.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] They are also widely used as driven elements for rooftop Yagi television antennas.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The T²FD antenna is a folded dipole with a resistor added on the second wire, opposite the feedpoint.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The folded dipole is therefore well matched to 300 Ω balanced transmission lines, such as twin-feed ribbon cable.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The folded dipole has a wider bandwidth than a single dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] They can be used for transforming the value of input impedance of the dipole over a broad range of step-up ratios by changing the thicknesses of the wire conductors for the fed- and folded-sides.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Instead of altering thickness or spacing, one can add a third parallel wire to increase the feedpoint impedance to 9 times that of a single-wire dipole, raising the impedance to 658 Ω, making a good match for open wire feed cable, and further broadening the resonant frequency band of the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] where $\ n\$ is the number of parallel halfwave-long wires laid side-by-side in the antenna, and connected at their ends.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The loading wire length is equal to the single missing length of one of the parallel wires.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] There are numerous modifications to the shape of a dipole antenna which are useful in one way or another but result in similar radiation characteristics (low gain).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] This is not to mention the many directional antennas which include one or more dipole elements in their design as driven elements, many of which are linked to in the information box at the bottom of this page.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] One implementation uses cage elements (see above); the thickness of the resulting elements lowers the high driving point impedance of a full-wave dipole to a value that accommodates a reasonable match to open wire lines and increases the bandwidth (in terms of SWR) to a full octave.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] They are used for HF band transmissions.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The *vertical*, *Marconi*, or monopole antenna is a single-element antenna usually fed at the bottom (with the shield side of its unbalanced transmission line connected to ground).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] It behaves essentially the same as half of a dipole antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The ground (or ground plane) is considered to be a conductive surface that works as a reflector (see effect of ground).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Vertical currents in the reflected image have the same direction (thus are *not* reflected about the ground) and phase as the current in the real antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The conductor and its image together act as a dipole in the upper half of space.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Like a dipole, in order to achieve resonance (resistive feedpoint impedance) the conductor must be close to a quarter wavelength in height (like each conductor in a half-wave dipole).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] In this upper side of space, the emitted field has the same amplitude of the field radiated by a similar dipole fed with the same current.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Therefore, the total emitted power is half the emitted power of a dipole fed with the same current.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] As the current is the same, the radiation resistance (real part of series impedance) will be half of the series impedance of the comparable dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Since the fields above ground are the same as for the dipole, but only half the power is applied, the gain is doubled to 5.14 dBi .
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] This is not an actual performance advantage *per se*, since in practice a dipole also reflects half of its power off the ground which (depending on the antenna height and sky angle) can augment (or cancel!) the direct signal.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The vertical polarization of the monopole (as for a vertically oriented dipole) is advantageous at low elevation angles where the ground reflection combines with the direct wave approximately in phase.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The earth acts as a ground plane, but it can be a poor conductor leading to losses.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Its conductivity can be improved (at cost) by laying a copper mesh.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] When an actual ground is not available (such as in a vehicle) other metallic surfaces can serve as a ground plane (typically the vehicle's roof).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Alternatively, radial wires placed at the base of the antenna can form a ground plane.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] For VHF and UHF bands, the radiating and ground plane elements can be constructed from rigid rods or tubes.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Using such an artificial ground plane allows for the entire antenna and ground to be mounted at an arbitrary height.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] One common modification has the radials forming the ground plane sloped down, which has the effect of raising the feedpoint impedance to around 50 Ω, matching common coaxial cable.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] No longer being a true ground, a balun (such as a simple choke balun) is then recommended.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The feedpoint impedance of a dipole antenna is sensitive to its electrical length and feedpoint position.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Therefore, a dipole will generally only perform optimally over a rather narrow bandwidth, beyond which its impedance will become a poor match for the transmitter or receiver (and transmission line).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The real (resistive) and imaginary (reactive) components of that impedance, as a function of electrical length, are shown in the accompanying graph.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The detailed calculation of these numbers are described below.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Note that the value of the reactance is highly dependent on the diameter of the conductors; this plot is for conductors with a diameter of 0.001 wavelengths.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Dipoles that are much smaller than one half the wavelength of the signal are called *short dipoles*.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] These have a very low radiation resistance (and a high capacitive reactance) making them inefficient antennas.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] More of a transmitter's current is dissipated as heat due to the finite resistance of the conductors which is greater than the radiation resistance.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] However they can nevertheless be practical receiving antennas for longer wavelengths.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Dipoles whose length is approximately half the wavelength of the signal are called *half-wave dipoles* and are widely used as such or as the basis for derivative antenna designs.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] These have a radiation resistance which is much greater, closer to the characteristic impedances of available transmission lines, and normally much larger than the resistance of the conductors, so that their efficiency approaches 100%.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] In general radio engineering, the term *dipole*, if not further qualified, is taken to mean a center-fed half-wave dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A true half-wave dipole is one half of the wavelength λ in length, where *λ* = ⁠*c*/ *f* ⁠ in free space.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Such a dipole has a feedpoint impedance consisting of 73 Ω resistance and +43 Ω reactance, thus presenting a slightly inductive reactance.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] where λ is the free-space wavelength, c is the speed of light in free space, and f is the frequency.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The adjustment factor k which causes feedpoint reactance to be eliminated, depends on the diameter of the conductor, as is plotted in the accompanying graph.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The relative scale-size k ranges from about 0.98 for thin wires (diameter, 0.00001 wave) to about 0.94 for thick conductors (diameter, 0.008 wave).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] This is because the effect of antenna length on reactance (upper graph) is much greater for thinner conductors so that a smaller deviation from the exact half wavelength is required in order to cancel the 43 Ω inductive reactance it has when exactly ⁠1/ 2 ⁠ λ .
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] For the same reason, antennas with thicker conductors have a wider operating bandwidth over which they attain a practical standing wave ratio which is degraded by any remaining reactance.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] For a typical k of about 0.95, the above formula for the corrected antenna length can be written, for a length in meters as ⁠143/ f ⁠, or a length in feet as ⁠468/ f ⁠ where f is the frequency in megahertz.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Dipole antennas of lengths approximately equal to any *odd* multiple of ⁠1/ 2 ⁠λ are also resonant, presenting little or no reactance (which can be removed by making a small length adjustment).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] One size that is a much more efficient radiator both in terms of Watts out and in direction radiated is a dipole with a length of ⁠5/ 4 ⁠ wave.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Not being close to ⁠3/ 2 ⁠ wave, this antenna's impedance has a large (negative) reactance and can only be used with an inductive impedance matching network (a tapped loading coil or a so-called antenna tuner).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] It is a desirable length because such an antenna has the highest gain for any dipole which isn't a great deal longer.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Three dimensional radiation pattern of a vertical half-wave dipole antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Radiation pattern of vertical half-wave dipole; vertical section.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A dipole is omnidirectional in the plane perpendicular to the wire axis, with the radiation falling to zero on the axis (off the ends of the antenna).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] In a half-wave dipole, the radiation is maximum perpendicular to the antenna, declining as $\ (\ \sin \theta \ )^{2}\$ to zero on the axis.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Its radiation pattern in three dimensions (see figure) would be plotted approximately as a toroid (doughnut shape) symmetric about the conductor.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] When mounted vertically this results in maximum radiation in horizontal directions.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] When mounted horizontally, the radiation peaks at right angles (90°) to the conductor, with nulls in the direction of the dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Neglecting electrical inefficiency, the antenna gain is equal to the directive gain, which is 1.50 (1.76 dBi or -0.39 dBd) for a short dipole, increasing to 1.64 (2.15 dBi or 0 dBd) for a half-wave dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] For a ⁠5/ 4 ⁠ wave dipole the gain further increases to about 5.2 dBi, making this length desirable for that reason even though the antenna is then off-resonance.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Longer dipoles than that have radiation patterns that are multi-lobed, with poorer gain (unless they are *much* longer) even along the strongest lobe.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Other enhancements to the dipole (such as including a corner reflector or an array of dipoles) can be considered when more substantial directivity is desired.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Such antenna designs, although based on the half-wave dipole, generally acquire their own names.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Ideally, a half-wave dipole should be fed using a balanced transmission line matching its typical 65–70 Ω input impedance.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Twin lead with a similar impedance is available but seldom used and does not match the balanced antenna terminals of most radio and television receivers.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Much more common is the use of common 300 Ω twin lead in conjunction with a *folded dipole*.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The driving point impedance of a half-wave folded dipole is 4 times that of a simple half-wave dipole, thus closely matching that 300 Ω characteristic impedance.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Most FM broadcast band tuners and older analog televisions include balanced 300 Ω antenna input terminals.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] However twin lead has the drawback that it is electrically disturbed by any other nearby conductor (including earth); when used for transmitting, care must be taken not to place it near other conductors.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Many types of coaxial cable (or coax) have a characteristic impedance of 75 Ω, which would otherwise be a good match for a half-wave dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] However, coax is a single-ended line whereas a center-fed dipole expects a balanced line (such as twin lead).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] By symmetry, one can see that the dipole's terminals have an equal but opposite voltage, whereas coax has one conductor grounded.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Using coax regardless results in an unbalanced line, in which the currents along the two conductors of the transmission line are no longer equal and opposite.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Since you then have a *net current* along the transmission line, the transmission line becomes an antenna itself, with unpredictable results (since it depends on the path of the transmission line).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] This will generally alter the antenna's intended radiation pattern, and change the impedance seen at the transmitter or receiver.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A balun is required to use coaxial cable with a dipole antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The balun transfers power between the single-ended coax and the balanced antenna, sometimes with an additional change in impedance.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A balun can be implemented as a transformer which also allows for an impedance transformation.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] This is usually wound on a ferrite toroidal core.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The toroid core material must be suitable for the frequency of use, and in a transmitting antenna it must be of sufficient size to avoid saturation.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Other balun designs are mentioned below.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A current balun uses a transformer wound on a toroid or rod of magnetic material such as ferrite.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] All of the current seen at the input goes into one terminal of the balanced antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] It forms a balun by choking common-mode current.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The material isn't critical for 1:1 because there is no transformer action applied to the desired differential current.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A related design involves *two* transformers and includes a 1:4 impedance transformation.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A coax balun is a cost-effective method of eliminating feeder radiation but is limited to a narrow set of operating frequencies.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] One easy way to make a balun is to use a length of coaxial cable equal to half a wavelength.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The inner core of the cable is linked at each end to one of the balanced connections for a feeder or dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] One of these terminals should be connected to the inner core of the coaxial feeder.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] All three braids should be connected together.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] This then forms a 4:1 balun, which works correctly at only a narrow band of frequencies.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] At VHF frequencies, a sleeve balun can also be built to remove feeder radiation.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Another narrow-band design is to use a ⁠1/ 4 ⁠ λ length of metal pipe.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The coaxial cable is placed inside the pipe; at one end the braid is wired to the pipe while at the other end no connection is made to the pipe.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The balanced end of this balun is at the end where no connection is made to the pipe.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The ⁠1/ 4 ⁠ λ conductor acts as a transformer, converting the zero impedance at the short to the braid into an infinite impedance at the open end.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] This infinite impedance at the open end of the pipe prevents current flowing into the outer coax formed by the outside of the inner coax shield and the pipe, forcing the current to remain in the inside coax.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] This balun design is impractical for low frequencies because of the long length of pipe that will be needed.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] One of the most common applications of the dipole antenna is the *rabbit ears* or *bunny ears* television antenna, found atop broadcast television receivers.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] It is used to receive the VHF terrestrial television bands, consisting in the US of 54–88 MHz (band I) and 174–216 MHz (band III), with wavelengths of 5.5–1.4 meters (18 feet to 4 feet 8 inches).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Since this frequency range is much wider than a single fixed dipole antenna can cover, it is made with several degrees of adjustment.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] It is constructed of two telescoping rods that can each be extended out to about 1 meters (3 feet) length (one-quarter wavelength at 75 MHz).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] With control over the segments' length, angle with respect to vertical, and compass angle, one has much more flexibility in optimizing reception than available with a rooftop antenna even if equipped with an antenna rotor.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] In contrast to the wide television frequency bands, the FM broadcast band (88-108 MHz) is narrow enough that a dipole antenna can cover it.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] For fixed use in homes, hi-fi tuners are typically supplied with simple folded dipoles resonant near the center of that band.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The feedpoint impedance of a folded dipole, which is quadruple the impedance of a simple dipole, is a good match for 300 Ω twin lead, so that is usually used for the transmission line to the tuner.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A common construction is to make the arms of the folded dipole out of twin lead also, shorted at their ends.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] This flexible antenna can be conveniently taped or nailed to walls, following the contours of moldings.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Horizontal wire dipole antennas are popular for use on the HF shortwave bands, both for transmitting and shortwave listening.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] They are usually constructed of two lengths of wire joined by a strain insulator in the center, which is the feedpoint.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The ends can be attached to existing buildings, structures, or trees, taking advantage of their heights.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] If used for transmitting, it is essential that the ends of the antenna be attached to supports through strain insulators with a sufficiently high flashover voltage, since the antenna's high-voltage antinodes occur there.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Being a balanced antenna, they are best fed with a balun between the (coax) transmission line and the feedpoint.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] These are simple to put up for temporary or field use.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] But they are also widely used by radio amateurs and short wave listeners in fixed locations due to their simple (and inexpensive) construction, while still realizing a resonant antenna at frequencies where resonant antenna elements need to be of quite some size.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] They are an attractive solution for these frequencies, when significant directionality is not desired, and the cost of several such resonant antennas for different frequency bands, built at home, may still be much less than a single commercially produced antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Antennas for MF and LF radio stations are usually constructed as mast radiators, in which the vertical mast itself forms the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Although mast radiators are most commonly monopoles, some are dipoles.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The metal structure of the mast is divided at its midpoint into two insulated sections to make a vertical dipole, which is driven at the midpoint.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Many types of array antennas are constructed using multiple dipoles, usually half-wave dipoles.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The purpose of using multiple dipoles is to increase the directional gain of the antenna over the gain of a single dipole; the radiation of the separate dipoles interferes to enhance power radiated in desired directions.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] In arrays with multiple dipole driven elements, the feedline is split using an electrical network in order to provide power to the elements, with careful attention paid to the relative phase delays due to transmission between the common point and each element.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] In order to increase antenna gain in horizontal directions (at the expense of radiation towards the sky or towards the ground) one can stack antennas in the vertical direction in a broadside array where the antennas are fed in phase.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Doing so with horizontal dipole antennas retains those dipoles' directionality and null in the direction of their elements.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] However, if each dipole is vertically oriented, in a so-called collinear antenna array (see graphic), that null direction becomes vertical and the array acquires an omnidirectional radiation pattern (in the horizontal plane) as is typically desired.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Vertical collinear arrays are used in the VHF and UHF frequency bands at which wavelengths the size of the elements are small enough to practically stack several on a mast.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] They are a higher-gain alternative to quarter-wave ground plane antennas used in fixed base stations for mobile two-way radios, such as police, fire, and taxi dispatchers.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] On the other hand, for a rotating antenna (or one used only towards a particular direction) one may desire increased gain and directivity in a particular horizontal direction.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] If the broadside array discussed above (whether collinear or not) is turned horizontal, then the one obtains a greater gain in the horizontal direction perpendicular to the antennas, at the expense of most other directions.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Unfortunately, that also means that the direction *opposite* the desired direction also has a high gain, whereas high gain is usually desired in one single direction.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] An alternative realization of a uni-directional antenna is the *end-fire array*.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] In this case the dipoles are again side by side (but not collinear), but fed in progressing phases, arranged so that their waves add coherently in one direction but cancel in the opposite direction.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] So now, rather than being perpendicular to the array direction as in a broadside array, the directivity is *in* the array direction (i.e. the direction of the line connecting their feedpoints) but with one of the opposite directions suppressed.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] The above-described antennas with multiple driven elements require a complex feed system of signal splitting, phasing, distribution to the elements, and impedance matching.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] A different sort of end-fire array which is much more often used is based on the use of so-called *parasitic elements*.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] In the popular high-gain Yagi antenna, only one of the dipoles is actually connected electrically, but the others receive and reradiate power supplied by the driven element.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] This time, the phasing is accomplished by careful choice of the lengths as well as positions of the parasitic elements, in order to concentrate gain in one direction and largely cancel radiation in the opposite direction (as well as all other directions).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Although the realized gain is less than a driven array with the same number of elements, the simplicity of the electrical connections makes the Yagi more practical for consumer applications.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] Antenna gain is frequently measured as decibels relative to a half-wave dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] One reason is that practical antenna measurements need a reference strength to compare the field strength of an antenna under test at a particular distance to.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] While there is no such thing as an isotropic radiator, the half-wave dipole is well understood and behaved, and can be constructed to be nearly 100% efficient.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] It is also a fairer comparison, since the gain obtained by the dipole itself is essentially "free," given that almost no antenna design has a smaller directive gain.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] For a gain measured relative to a dipole, one says the antenna has a gain of "x dBd" (see Decibel).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] More often, gains are expressed relative to an isotropic radiator, making the gain seem higher.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p01] In consideration of the known gain of a half-wave dipole, 0 dBd is defined as 2.15 dBi; all gains in "dBi" are shifted 2.15 higher than gains in "dBd".
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] The Hertzian dipole may be defined as a finite oscillating current (in a specified direction) of $\ I\ e^{i\omega t}\$ over a tiny or infinitesimal length $\ \delta \ell \$ at a specified position.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] As a function of position, taking the elementary current elements $\ I\!\left(\mathbf {r} \right)\ ,$ multiplied by infinitesimal lengths $\ \delta \ell \ ,$ the resulting field pattern then reduces to an integral over the path of an antenna conductor (modeled as a thin wire).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] For the following derivation, we shall take the current to be in the $\ z\$ direction, centered at the origin where $\ x=y=z=0\ ,$ with the sinusoidal time dependence $\ e^{i\omega t}\$ for all quantities being understood.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] The simplest approach is to use the calculation of the vector potential $\ \mathbf {A} \!\left(\mathbf {r} \right)\$ using the formula for the retarded potential.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] where $\ \mu _{0}\$ is the permeability of free space.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] This solution includes near field terms that are very strong near the source but which are not radiated.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] As seen in the accompanying animation, the $\ \mathbf {E} \$ and $\ \mathbf {H} \$ fields very close to the source are almost 90° out of phase, thus contributing very little to the Poynting vector by which radiated flux is computed.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] The near field solution for an antenna element (from the integral using this formula over the length of that element) is the field that can be used to compute the mutual impedance between it and another nearby element.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] The far-field pattern is thus seen to consist of a transverse electromagnetic (TEM) wave, with electric and magnetic fields at right angles to each other and at right angles to the direction of propagation (the direction of $\ \mathbf {r} \$ , as we assumed the source to be at the origin).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] The electric polarization, in the $\theta$ direction, is coplanar with the source current (in the $\ z\$ direction), while the magnetic field is at right angles to that, in the $\ \phi \$ direction.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] It can be seen from these equations, and also in the animation, that the fields at these distances are exactly *in phase*.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] Both fields fall according to ${\textstyle \ {\frac {\ 1\ }{r}}\ ,}$ with the power thus falling according to ${\textstyle \ {\frac {1}{\ r^{2}}}\ }$ as dictated by the inverse square law.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] If one knows the far field radiation pattern due to a given antenna current, then it is possible to compute the radiation resistance directly.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] With increasing $\ r\$ the $\ \langle S_{\mathsf {\phi }}\rangle \$ becomes insignificantly small compared to the $\ \langle S_{\mathsf {r}}\rangle \$ component.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] This method can be used to compute the radiation resistance for any antenna whose far-field radiation pattern has been found in terms of a specific antenna current.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] If ohmic losses in the conductors are neglected, the radiation resistance (considered relative to the feedpoint) is identical to the resistive (real) component of the feedpoint impedance.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] Unfortunately, this exercise tells us nothing about the reactive (imaginary) component of feedpoint impedance, whose calculation is considered below.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] Using the above expression for the radiated flux given by the Poynting vector, it is also possible to compute the directive gain of the Hertzian dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] The commonly quoted antenna "gain", meaning the peak value of the gain pattern (radiation pattern), is found to be 1.5~1.76 dBi, lower than practically any other antenna configuration.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] The Hertzian dipole is *similar to* but differs from the short dipole, discussed above.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] In both cases the conductor is very short compared to a wavelength, so the standing wave pattern present on a half-wave dipole (for instance) is absent.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] However, with the Hertzian dipole we specified that the current along that conductor is *constant* over its short length.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] This makes the Hertzian dipole useful for analysis of more complex antenna configurations, where every infinitesimal section of that *real* antenna's conductor can be modeled as a Hertzian dipole with the current found to be flowing in that real antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] However a short conductor fed with a RF voltage will not have a uniform current even along that short range.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] Rather, a short dipole in real life has a current equal to the feedpoint current at the feedpoint but falling linearly to zero over the length of that short conductor.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] By placing a *capacitive hat*, such as a metallic ball, at the end of the conductor, it is possible for its self capacitance to absorb the current from the conductor and better approximate the constant current assumed for the Hertzian dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] But again, the Hertzian dipole is meant only as a theoretical construct for antenna analysis.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] But their radiation patterns (and gains) are otherwise identical.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] The impedance seen at the feedpoint of a dipole of various lengths has been plotted above, in terms of the real (resistive) component Rdipole and the imaginary (reactive) component j Xdipole of that impedance.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] For the case of an antenna with perfect conductors (no Ohmic loss), Rdipole is identical to the radiation resistance, which can more easily be computed from the total power in the far-field radiation pattern for a given applied current as we showed for the short dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] The calculation of Xdipole is more difficult.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] Using the *induced EMF method* closed form expressions are obtained for both components of the feedpoint impedance; such results are plotted above.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] The solution depends on an assumption for the form of the current distribution along the antenna conductors.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] where k is the wavenumber given by *k* = ⁠2 *π*/ *λ* ⁠ = ⁠2 *π f*/ *c* ⁠ , and the amplitude A is set to match a specified driving point current at *z* = 0 .
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] In cases where an approximately sinusoidal current distribution can be assumed, this method solves for the driving point impedance in closed form using the cosine and sine integral functions Si(*x*) and Ci(*x*) .
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] where a is the radius of the conductors, k is again the wavenumber as defined above, ζ0 is the impedance of empty space, which very nearly the same as impedance of air: ζ0 ≈ 377 Ω , and $\ \gamma _{e}=0.57721566\ \ldots \$ is Euler's constant.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] There is an equivalent alternate form favored by some authors that uses a different function, Cin .
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] The induced EMF method is dependent on the assumption of a sinusoidal current distribution, delivering an accuracy better than about 10% as long as the wavelength-to-element diameter ratio is greater than about 60.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] However, for yet larger conductors numerical solutions are required which solve for the conductor's current distribution (rather than *assuming* a sinusoidal pattern).
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] This can be based on approximating solutions for either *Pocklington's integrodifferential equation* or the *Hallén integral equation*.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] These approaches also have greater generality, not being limited to linear conductors.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] Numerical solution of either is performed using the *moment method solution* which requires expansion of that current into a set of basis functions; one simple (but not the best) choice, for instance, is to break up the conductor into N segments with a constant current assumed along each.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] After setting an appropriate weighting function the cost may be minimized through the inversion of a *N*×*N* matrix.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] Determination of each matrix element requires at least one double integration involving the weighting functions, which may become computationally intensive.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] These are simplified if the weighting functions are simply delta functions, which corresponds to fitting the boundary conditions for the current along the conductor at only N discrete points.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] Then the *N*×*N* matrix must be inverted, which is also computationally intensive as N increases.
[src:antenna-theory/dipole-antenna-p02] In one simple example, Balanis (2011) performs this computation to find the antenna impedance with different N using Pocklington's method, and finds that with *N* > 60 the solutions approach their limiting values to within a few percent.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] A **monopole antenna** is a class of radio antenna consisting of a straight rod-shaped conductor, often mounted perpendicularly over some type of conductive surface, called a ground plane.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The current from the transmitter is applied, or for receiving antennas the output signal voltage to the receiver is taken, between the monopole and the ground plane.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] One side of the feedline to the transmitter or receiver is connected to the lower end of the monopole element, and the other side is connected to the ground plane, which may be the Earth.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This contrasts with a dipole antenna which consists of two identical rod conductors, with the current from the transmitter applied between the two halves of the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The monopole antenna is related mathematically to the dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The vertical monopole is an omnidirectional antenna with a low gain of 2 - 5 dBi, and radiates most of its power in horizontal directions or low elevation angles.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Common types of monopole antenna are the whip, rubber ducky, umbrella, inverted-L and T-antenna, inverted-F, folded unipole antenna, mast radiator, and ground plane antennas.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The monopole is usually used as a resonant antenna; the rod functions as an open resonator for radio waves, oscillating with standing waves of voltage and current along its length.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Therefore the length of the antenna is determined by the wavelength of the radio waves it is used with.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The most common form is the *quarter-wave monopole*, in which the antenna is approximately one quarter of the wavelength of the radio waves.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] It is said to be the most widely used antenna in the world.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Monopoles shorter than one-quarter wavelength, called *electrically short* monopoles, are also widely used since they are more compact.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Monopoles five-eights (5/8 = 0.625) of a wavelength long are also common, because at this length a monopole radiates a maximum amount of its power in horizontal directions.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] A *capacitively loaded* or *top-loaded* monopole is a monopole antenna with horizontal conductors such as wires or screens insulated from ground attached to the top of the monopole element, to increase radiated power.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Large top-loaded monopoles, the T and inverted L antennas and umbrella antenna are used as transmitting antennas at longer wavelengths, in the LF and VLF bands.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The monopole antenna was invented in 1895 by radio pioneer Guglielmo Marconi; for this reason it is also called the *Marconi antenna* although Alexander Popov independently invented it at about the same time.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The quarter-wave monopole is the smallest antenna that is resonant, making it an efficient radiator; it is said to be the most widely used antenna in the world.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Large monopoles are the main transmitting antennas used in the lower frequencies below 3 MHz, the MF, LF, and VLF bands, because the radio propagation mode used in these bands, ground waves, requires a vertically polarized antenna with good horizontal radiation characteristics.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] At these frequencies, the Earth itself is used as the antenna's ground plane.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The most common antenna is the mast radiator, a vertical mast mounted on the ground but insulated from it electrically. ranging from about one-sixth to five-eighths wavelengths tall.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] One side of the feedline from the transmitter is connected to the conductive metal mast which serves as the radiating element, and the other to an Earth ground connection consisting of a radial network of buried wires stretching outward from a terminal at the base of the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This design is used for AM radio broadcasting antennas in the MF and LF bands.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Another variant is the folded unipole antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] At lower frequencies in the LF and VLF band, the tallest antenna masts that can be practically constructed are electrically short, significantly shorter than one-quarter wavelength.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Simple monopoles this short are inefficient due to their very low radiation resistance, so to increase efficiency and radiated power, capacitively top-loaded monopoles such as the inverted-L, T antenna and umbrella antenna are used.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] In the shortwave bands variations such as the folded monopole, J-pole antenna, and normal mode helical are used.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] At higher frequencies in the VHF and UHF bands, the size of the ground plane needed is smaller, so artificial metal ground planes of screen or rods are used to allow the antenna to be mounted above the ground.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] A common type for mounting on masts or stationary structures is the ground plane antenna, consisting of a quarter-wave whip antenna with a ground plane of 3 or 4 wires or rods a quarter-wavelength long radiating horizontally or diagonally from its base, connected to the ground side of the feedline.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Another variation is the discone antenna, which is notable for having a very broad bandwidth.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The quarter-wave whip and rubber ducky antennas used with handheld radios such as walkie-talkies and portable FM radios in the VHF and UHF bands are also monopole antennas.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] In these portable devices the antenna does not have an effective ground plane, the ground side of the transmitter or receiver is just connected to the chassis ground connection on its circuit board.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Since these "ground" conductors are no larger than the element itself the antenna usually functions more like an asymmetrical dipole than a monopole antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] A monopole type widely used in wireless devices and cell phones operating at microwave frequencies is the inverted F antenna (IFA).
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The monopole element is bent over in an L shape parallel to the ground area on the circuit board, to make it compact enough to be enclosed in the device case; the antenna may be fabricated of copper foil on the printed circuit board itself.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] To improve the impedance match with the feed circuit the antenna is *shunt fed*, the feedline is connected to an intermediate point along the element, and the base of the element is grounded.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Many variants of this antenna are used in handheld devices, such as multiband versions and meander antennas.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Metal sheets and spark balls not shown to scale.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Later he found that the plates were unnecessary and a suspended wire was adequate.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] One of Marconi's early monopole antennas at his Poldhu, Cornwall transmitting station, 1900, consisting of a small metal plate suspended from a wooden arm with a long wire running down to the transmitter in the building.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The monopole antenna was invented in 1895 and patented in 1896 by radio entrepreneur Guglielmo Marconi during his first experiments in radio communication.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] He began by using dipole antennas invented by Heinrich Hertz consisting of two identical horizontal wires ending in metal plates, and by his mentor Augusto Righi consisting of four metal spark balls, but was unable to transmit further than about a half mile.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] He found by experiment that if instead of the dipole, one side of the transmitter and receiver terminals was connected to a wire attached to a metal plate suspended overhead, and the other side was connected to a conductor buried in the Earth, he could transmit for longer distances.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] He found the plate was unnecessary and a suspended wire was adequate.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The monopole is also called a *Marconi antenna*, although Alexander Popov independently invented it at about the same time for his lightning detection receiver.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] In the next few years, using higher monopole antennas and better transmitters and receivers Marconi steadily increased the range of his radiotelegraphy communication system to hundreds of kilometers (miles), convincing the world that radio was a practical communication method.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] In 1901 he achieved transatlantic radio transmission using a monopole transmitting antenna consisting of 50 vertical wires suspended in a fan shape from a support cable between 60 meter (200 foot) poles.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Before Marconi, several inventors experimented with wireless communication between vertical aerials, although without creating a practical system.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] In October 1866 Mahlon Loomis demonstrated communication between two grounded 183-meter (600-foot) wire aerials supported by kites on mountaintops 22 kilometres (14 miles) apart.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] When one aerial wire was touched to a grounded contact, currents of atmospheric electricity in it apparently generated radio waves which induced currents in the other wire, detected by a sensitive galvanometer.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Starting in 1882, Amos Dolbear also used grounded vertical wire antennas during his development of a ground conduction telephone, but his system seems to have worked by electrostatic induction instead of radio waves, and by 1895 he had only achieved distances of 1/4 mile.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] A suit claiming Marconi infringed Dolbear's 1882 and 1886 wireless patents was dismissed in 1901.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] In 1885 Thomas Edison patented a system of harbor communication between vertical towers on shore and vertical wires suspended from a ship's mast, but this also worked by electrostatic induction and was never tried.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] In the primitive spark transmitters used in Marconi's time, in addition to radiating the radio waves the antenna also served as the resonator which generated the oscillating currents which determine the frequency and thus the wavelength of the waves.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Marconi's new antenna functioned as a quarter-wave monopole which radiated with a wavelength of approximately four times its height.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This longer antenna greatly increased the wavelength, reducing the frequency of Marconi’s transmitter from the VHF and UHF bands generated by Hertz's antennas which could not transmit beyond the horizon, to the MF band.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Also, it emitted vertically polarized radio waves, instead of the horizontally polarized waves produced by the Hertz antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Longer radio waves have less attenuation with distance.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] These longer vertically polarized waves could propagate as ground waves which can follow the curvature of the Earth, and could also reflect off the ionosphere (called the 'skip' or skywave mechanism), and thus travel beyond the visual horizon.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Marconi, who was self-educated in physics, did not understand any of this at the time; he merely discovered an empirical relation between antenna height and transmission distance.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Moisè Ascoli of Rome with first calculating in 1897 that the antenna radiated at a wavelength of four times its height.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] An integral equation for the current in wire antennas was derived by Henry Pocklington in 1897, who showed the current was approximately a sinusoidal standing wave.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Around 1898 André Blondel used image theory to show that the monopole had the same radiation pattern as a vertical dipole antenna of twice the length.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] A more useful version of the Pocklington equation, the Hallen equation, was derived by Erik Hallén beginning in 1938.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] These integral equations are the starting point in modern analyses of monopoles, and are solved numerically in modern computer antenna simulation programs.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] During the radiotelegraphy era, the first two decades of radio from 1900 until the 1920s, radio communication systems used long wavelengths above 200 meters (frequencies below 1.5 MHz), in the MF, LF and VLF bands.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] At the longer wavelengths used for long distance communication the tallest antenna masts that could be practically constructed were much shorter than the resonant length, one-quarter wavelength.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Monopole antennas this short are inefficient; due to their low radiation resistance of 5 to 20 ohms, a large fraction of the transmitter power was wasted in the ground system resistance.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The main technique known for increasing radiated power was to add conductors to the top of the antenna, to increase the capacitance to ground and thus the antenna current.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Marconi and others developed huge multiwire capacitively top-loaded monopole antennas which were more efficient at these frequencies, such as the harp, inverted cone, inverted L, T antenna and umbrella antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] These were the main antennas during this period, and the latter three are still the main transmitting antennas used at these low frequencies.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] When radio broadcasting began in the MF band in the early 1920s, the typical transmitting antenna was the T-antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This required two masts, an extensive land area, and currents in the masts distorted the radiation pattern.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Two papers published in 1924 by Stuart Ballantine led to the adoption of the single-mast monopole radiator.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] One derived the radiation resistance of a vertical monopole antenna over a perfect ground plane.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] In a second paper the same year he showed that the amount of power radiated horizontally in ground waves reached a maximum at a mast height of 5/8 wavelength (.625 $\lambda$ ).
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Due to these discoveries, by 1930 the disadvantages of the T antenna led broadcasters to adopt the half-wave mast radiator antenna in the medium frequency band.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Radial wire ground systems were developed at the same time to reduce ground losses.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The advent of handheld radios in the 1950s and 1960s, the transistor radio and walkie-talkie, made possible by the invention of the transistor in 1947, motivated the development of compact monopole antennas for them, like the retractable quarter-wave whip and the rubber ducky antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] A monopole antenna, like the dipole antenna from which it is derived, is a resonant antenna; it not only emits and receives radio waves but acts as an electrical resonator.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] When the radio frequency alternating current applied to its feedpoint is near one of its resonant frequencies, in addition to radiating the power as radio waves, energy is stored in the antenna as oscillating electric currents called standing waves.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The advantage of this is that the stored energy is larger than the energy fed to the antenna each cycle by the transmitter (or in a receiving antenna the energy absorbed from the radio waves), so most of the current in the antenna is due to this stored energy.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] As a result the antenna current at resonance is larger than the current when the antenna is driven at other frequencies.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The radio wave power radiated by an antenna is proportional to the square of the antenna current, so an antenna fed at a resonant frequency radiates much more power than the same antenna fed with the same voltage at some other frequency.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] An antenna only absorbs all the input power from the feedline when it is in a condition of resonance.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The vertical conductor acts somewhat like a transmission line stub, open-circuited at the top.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The oscillation modes are analogous to the mechanical oscillations of an elastic beam anchored at one end.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The current and voltage along the element are sinusoidal waves.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The current in the antenna element bounces back and forth between the ends, and the two equal but opposite current waves interfere to form a standing wave.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The standing wave has a current node at its top and either a node or an antinode at bottom.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Due to these end conditions the monopole is resonant (has pure resistive input impedance) at a length of a quarter wavelength or multiples of it.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] If the top of the rod is negatively charged and the ground plane positively charged at the beginning of the cycle, the current begins to flow up the rod from the ground plane, creating a circular magnetic field around the rod.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The negative charge at the top and positive charge on the ground plane decrease until they reach zero.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] However the current continues, because the inductance of the rod resists changes in current.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The current begins to charge the top of the rod positive and the ground plane negative.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] From Faraday's law of induction the energy to create this separation of charge comes from the magnetic field, which decreases.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Finally when the magnetic field reaches zero the current stops with the charges reversed, the top of the rod is charged positive and the ground plane negative.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Then the current begins to flow in the opposite direction, down the rod, generating a magnetic field circling in the opposite direction, until the charges reverse again to their original polarity, with the top of the rod negative and the ground plane positive.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This oscillation keeps repeating, with the energy stored alternately in the electric field and the magnetic field each half-cycle of the applied alternating current.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Most of these coupled oscillating electric and magnetic fields are near fields (also called reactive or induction fields) which store energy in the space around the antenna, but some of the fields leave the antenna and travel away as electromagnetic waves, radio waves, carrying energy with them.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The radiated power is provided by incoming power from the feedline.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Due to this power loss, an antenna acts as if it has a resistance, the radiation resistance, at its feedpoint.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] As a result, a monopole acts electrically like a lossy tuned circuit; in general it has both electrical resistance and reactance at its feedpoint.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The input resistance has two components; the radiation resistance (normally the largest part) and the loss resistance due to ohmic losses in the antenna conductor and ground plane.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] At resonance the input impedance is just this pure resistance; at other frequencies it has reactance in addition to the resistance, and thus a higher impedance.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] A transmitting antenna will absorb all the power applied to its feedpoint only if it is conjugate impedance matched to the feedline from the transmitter.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This means the resistance of the antenna and line must be equal, and the reactance of antenna and line must be opposite.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] If it is not impedance matched, some of the transmitter power from the feedline will be reflected back down the line toward the transmitter, causing a high SWR, resulting in inefficiency and possibly overheating the transmitter or line, or causing arcing.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Similarly, a receiving antenna will only transfer a maximum amount of radio power to the receiver if it is impedance matched to the line.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Most monopoles have a conducting surface under the vertical rod, a *ground plane*, connected to the ground side of the feedline.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The ground plane is an integral part of the antenna; it has two functions.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] First, it reflects the downward directed radio waves from the rod, increasing the power radiated above the ground.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Second, it acts as a capacitor plate, receiving the displacement current (alternating electric field) from the rod, returning it to the ground side of the feedline.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Without it there will be induced currents on the outside of the shield conductor of the feedline, which will act as additional antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The current in the ground plane is radial, directed alternately toward and away from the ground terminal at the base of the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Therefore far from the antenna the radio waves radiated by the currents in opposite sides of the plane have opposite phase and largely cancel.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] So the plane itself does not radiate; it acts as a mirror for the radio waves from the rod.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The electric field is vertical where it enters the ground plane, identical to the field of a vertical dipole antenna at its symmetry plane.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] If the ground plane is large enough, due to the waves reflected from it the antenna acts as if it has an image antenna identical to the monopole underneath the plane.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The antenna rod and its image together act like a dipole antenna of twice the length, so a monopole over an infinite, perfectly conducting plane has a radiation pattern identical to the top half of the pattern of a vertical dipole of twice the length.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] For the quarter wave monopole, the antenna acts like a half wave dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Because the antenna only radiates its power into half the space of a dipole antenna, its gain is twice (or in decibels, 3 dB greater than) the gain of an equivalent dipole.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The actual gain and radiation pattern is dependent on the size and conductivity of the ground plane.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] To function as a mirror the plane must extend least a half wavelength from the monopole element.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Low frequency monopole transmitting antennas use the Earth itself as the ground plane.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] They require a good low resistance connection to the Earth for efficiency, since the soil has significant resistance which is in series with the antenna and consumes transmitter power.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] These use a *radial ground system* consisting of many bare copper wires buried shallowly in the earth, radiating from a ground terminal at the base of the antenna, preferably to a distance of a quarter to a half wavelength.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Because of the unbalanced impedance of the ground plane, monopole antennas are usually fed from an unbalanced transmission line, most often coaxial cable.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The *Pocklington integral equation* (Henry Pocklington, 1897) or *Hallen integral equation* (Erik Hallén, 1938) give the current on thin cylindrical antennas.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] In general, accurate calculation of an antenna's electrical properties is mathematically difficult, and antenna simulation computer programs like NEC are usually used.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] For smaller planes, for accurate results resonances in the ground plane and refraction around the edges must also be taken into account, so the current distribution in the plane must also be calculated.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The current in the monopole element is approximately a sinusoidal standing wave $I(z)$ composed of two superimposed traveling current waves, one $i_{\text{up}}(z,t)$ moving up the antenna and reflecting from the top, the other $i_{\text{down}}(z,t)$ moving down and reflecting from the ground plane.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This is the same as the Telegrapher's equation for a lossless transmission line, explaining why linear antennas behave like transmission lines.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Solving for the monopole element, and applying the boundary conditions $I(h)=0$ and for a base-fed antenna $I(0)=I_{\text{0}}$ , the peak radio frequency current $I(z)$ at a height of z on the monopole is approximately a sinusoidal standing wave with a node at the top.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] is the loop current, the current at the antinode of the standing wave.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] or longer it is the maximum current on the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The current is close to 90° out of phase with the feed voltage at the bottom.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] It lags the feed voltage in a transmitting antenna and leads the feed in a receiving antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This approximation assumes the Q factor of the antenna is much greater than one; in other words the stored energy is much larger than the feed energy per cycle which is equal to the radiated energy.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This is a good approximation for a thin antenna driven at resonance.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Although it is numerically accurate for a diameter-to-wavelength ratio $2b/\lambda$ less than 10−4, it is a good approximation up to $2b/\lambda <.05$ and applies qualitatively even to thick monopoles.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] For finite width monopoles the current does not quite go to zero at the nodes, and the 180 degree phase change there is not abrupt but occurs continuously over a short distance centered on the node.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Since this approximation assumes the energy applied by the feedline, and the energy lost to radiation, are negligible, the voltage across the feedline and the radiation resistance are implicitly assumed to be zero.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The current is the sum of two terms: the original sinusoidal wave which is 90° out of phase with the feed voltage, and a second smaller wave induced by the back reaction of the radiation fields on the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This wave is in phase with the feed voltage and supplies the radiated power.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Since at any point on the element this current must supply the power radiated by the portion of element above it, it decreases with height along the element to zero at the top.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] For most monopole antennas ohmic resistance is small, so the input resistance mainly consists of the radiation resistance $R_{\text{R}}$ .
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Over a perfectly conducting infinite ground plane, the input impedance of a monopole is half that of a center-fed dipole twice the length.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The impedance of a linear antenna can be found using the *induced EMF method* invented by Léon Brillouin, by calculating the near fields, and integrating the Poynting vector over the surface of the antenna rod.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The lines for a given length/diameter are colored the same in the two graphs.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] These equations are exact for an infinitely thin antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] A monopole antenna is resonant (has pure resistive input impedance, no reactance) at a series of frequencies, which depend on its length h .
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] These are important because it is easier to match the transmission line to the antenna at resonance.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] To find them precisely, antenna simulation computer programs must be used.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] However, for most monopole and dipole antennas in which the element is not excessively thick, the resonant frequencies are often calculated approximately by regarding the conductor as an open-ended single wire transmission line (resonant stub).
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] As in a resonant stub, the phase difference between the current and voltage standing waves is close to 90°.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This means the voltage standing wave has an antinode (maximum) at each current node (minimum), and a node (minimum) at each current antinode (maximum).
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The wave travels along the element at a velocity close to the speed of light c .
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Therefore the phase change in radians of the wave from one end of the element to the other is $kh=2\pi {h \over \lambda }$ .
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] For a round trip the phase change is twice this, $4\pi {h \over \lambda }$ .
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] At the ends of the element there can be an additional phase change, which depends on the end conditions.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The sine wave repeats every $2\pi$ radians (360°).
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The lowest resonant frequency, $f_{\text{0}}$ , at which the antenna is a quarter-wavelength ( $\lambda /4$ ) long, is called the *fundamental* resonance, while the higher resonances, which are multiples of the fundamental, are called *harmonics*.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] These are sometimes called the *series* resonant frequencies because near these frequencies the antenna acts similar electrically to a series resonant tuned circuit.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Because the feedpoint at the bottom of the antenna is a voltage node (minimum) and current antinode (maximum), at these frequencies the input impedance, equal to the ratio of voltage to current, is a minimum.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] For a $\lambda /4$ monopole it is 36.5 ohms (as shown below).
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The monopole can also resonate at a second series of lengths, at which the bottom end of the element is a current node (minimum) instead of a current antinode (maximum).
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] So the element has a node of the current standing wave at both top and bottom, it is equivalent to an end-fed vertical dipole antenna (so some sources do not call this antenna a monopole).
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The resonant frequencies can be calculated by a derivation similar to that in the previous section, but it is easier to note that a standing wave has a node at intervals of one-half wavelength.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] These are sometimes called *parallel* resonances or *antiresonances* because the antenna acts similar to a parallel resonant (antiresonant) tuned circuit.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] When fed at the bottom, due to the current node and voltage antinode there the antenna has a very high input resistance, which is difficult to calculate.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] For a hypothetical infinitely thin element it would be infinite, so there would be no input current.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] For a typical finite thickness monopole element it is around 700 - 3000 ohms depending on thickness.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] It also has a very high rate of change of reactance with frequency about the resonance point, which gives the antenna a narrower bandwidth than at the series resonances.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] To reduce the impedance enough to match a transmission line, either an impedance matching circuit or shunt feed must be used.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] An advantage is that since it acts as a dipole the current in the ground system is low, so ground losses are minimized; for thin antennas a ground plane is not needed at all.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Higher harmonics are little used since they have more complicated radiation patterns consisting of multiple lobes directed at angles into the sky with nulls (directions of minimum radiation) between them, resulting in locations with no reception.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] ), showing the spreading of field lines at top.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This causes more charge to be stored per unit length near the top of the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Fractional reduction of resonant length of monopole as a function of element diameter.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The resonant length decreases with increasing diameter of the element.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] ) of the standing wave moves further above the end of the element, so at a given frequency the antenna is resonant at a shorter length.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The exact lengths at which physical monopoles are resonant, found by solving the equation $X_{\text{R}}(h)=0$ above or by using antenna simulation programs, are a little shorter than the harmonic resonant lengths h calculated in the previous section, and depend on the element's diameter.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This is due to the shape of the electric field (fringing field) at the top end of the element (*A*) which spreads out in a fan (*see diagram*).
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] This adds capacitance and reduces the inductance at the end.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Due to this ability to store more charge per unit length, near the top the standing wave current profile (*I(z), red line*) differs from a sine wave, decreasing faster with height.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] When approximated as a sine wave (*blue line*), this is equivalent to the node of the standing wave (*N*) occurring not at the top of the antenna but some distance above it.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] So the resonant length of the element (*h*) is shorter than a multiple of one quarter of the free space wavelength $\lambda =c/f$ from the previous section.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The thicker the element is, the larger the end capacitance and the shorter the resonant length.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] Another common way of saying this is that the resonant frequencies depend on the *electrical length* of the element (length in wavelengths of the current in the conductor), not the *physical length* (length measured in wavelengths of the radio wave in free space).
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] The electrical length of a linear antenna is longer than its physical length, so the resonant frequencies are lower than would be calculated from its physical length.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] To make it resonant it can be shortened to .237 $\lambda$ at which length it has an input impedance of $34+j0$ ohms.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] In addition, anything which adds capacitance to the antenna element, such as the presence of grounded objects or high permittivity dielectric materials like insulating coatings or supporting electrical insulators near the end of the element will further decrease the resonant length.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] These are collectively called "end effects".
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] As can be seen from the reactance graph in the impedance section, at the half wavelength resonance the length/diameter ratio and other end effects have a much larger influence on the resonant length.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p01] In the rest of the article, when the *resonant length* of a monopole is mentioned, it is assumed to include this correction.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Like a vertical dipole antenna, a monopole has an omnidirectional radiation pattern: it radiates equal power in all azimuthal directions perpendicular to the antenna axis.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The radiated power varies with elevation angle, with the radiation dropping off to zero at the zenith on the antenna axis.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] It radiates vertically polarized radio waves, with the electric field parallel to the element.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] A monopole can be visualized *(see diagram)* as being formed by replacing the bottom half of a vertical dipole antenna *(c)* with a conducting plane (ground plane) at right-angles to the remaining half.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] If the ground plane is large enough, the radio waves from the remaining upper half of the dipole *(a)* reflected from the ground plane will seem to come from an image antenna *(b)* forming the missing half of the dipole, which adds to the direct radiation to form a dipole radiation pattern.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] So the pattern of a monopole over a perfectly conducting, infinite ground plane is identical to the top half of a dipole pattern.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Up to a length of a half-wavelength ( ${\lambda \over 2}$ ) the radiation pattern has a single donut-shaped lobe with maximum radiated power in horizontal directions, perpendicular to the antenna axis.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] As the length is increased above ${\lambda \over 4}$ the lobe flattens, radiating less power at high angles and more in horizontal directions.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Above a half-wavelength the pattern splits into a horizontal main lobe and a small second conical lobe at an angle of 60° elevation into the sky.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Above $.625\lambda$ the high angle lobe gets larger, becoming the main lobe, and the horizontal lobe rapidly gets smaller, reducing power radiated in horizontal directions, so very few antennas use lengths above this.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] At the 4th harmonic, $h=\lambda$ , the horizontal lobe disappears and all the power is radiated in the high angle lobe.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] As the antenna is made longer, the pattern divides into more lobes, with nulls (directions of zero radiated power) between them.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The general effect of electrically small ground planes, as well as imperfectly conducting earth grounds, is to tilt the direction of maximum radiation up to higher elevation angles and reduce the gain.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] With an asymmetrical ground plane, such as a whip antenna mounted on a car’s bumper, the pattern will no longer be omnidirectional, but will have stronger horizontal radiation on the side with the larger ground plane area.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Since a half-wave dipole has a gain of 2.19 dBi and a radiation resistance of 73.1 ohms, a quarter-wave ( $\lambda /4$ ) monopole will have a gain of 2.19 + 3 = 5.19 dBi and a radiation resistance of about 36.5 ohms.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The antenna is resonant at this length, so its input impedance is purely resistive.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The input impedance has capacitive reactance below $\lambda /4$ , inductive reactance from $\lambda /4$ to $\lambda /2$ , and capacitive reactance from $\lambda /2$ to $3\lambda /4$ .
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The gain figures given in the table above are never approached in practice; they would only be achieved if the antenna was mounted over an infinite perfectly conducting ground plane.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The ground plane is part of the antenna, and the gain is highly dependent on its size and conductivity.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Similarly over a resistive Earth ground the gain will be lower due to power absorbed in the Earth.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] For electrically short monopoles below $\lambda /4$ the gain decreases slowly; it is 4.76 dBi at $\lambda /20$ .
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] As the length is increased to a half-wavelength ( $\lambda /2$ ), the gain increases to about 1.7 dB over the $\lambda /4$ gain.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Since at this length the antenna has a current node at its feedpoint, the input impedance is very high.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The gain continues to increase up to a maximum of about 3 dB over a quarter-wave monopole at a length of five-eighths wavelength ( $.625\lambda$ ) so this is a popular length for ground wave antennas and terrestrial communication antennas.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The radiation resistance drops to about 53 ohms at that length.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Above $.625\lambda$ the horizontal gain drops rapidly because more power is radiated at high elevation angles in the second lobe.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The reason a vertical monopole has an omnidirectional radiation pattern is that it is axially symmetrical about the vertical axis.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The radiation pattern is given in spherical coordinates $r,\theta ,\phi$ , and due to this symmetry the pattern does not depend on the azimuth variable, $\phi$ .
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] As mentioned, the radiation pattern of the monopole is the same as the top half of the dipole pattern.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] For a radio antenna what is of interest is the radiation pattern in the far field region, far enough from the antenna so the induction fields have died out.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The Fraunhofer diffraction equation below is accurate when $r\gg h$ , $kr={2\pi r \over \lambda }\gg 1$ and $kh^{2}\ll 4\pi r$ , that is at distances from the antenna r much greater than the element length and the wavelength.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] is the distance from origin of the coordinate system at the base of the antenna to the reception point.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] is the angle with respect to the positive z axis, the axis of the element.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The electric field E given by this equation is a phasor, a complex number with magnitude equal to the peak field and angle equal to the phase difference between the sinusoidal field and the input current.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The presence of j at the front of the equation means that the electric and magnetic fields leave the antenna 90° out of phase with the feed current.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The advantage of this is that at different points on the antenna the input impedance has different values, allowing the possibility of impedance matching the antenna to the feedline characteristic impedance without a matching network, by choosing the correct feedpoint.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] A monopole shorter than the fundamental resonance length of a quarter-wavelength at its operating frequency is called *electrically short*.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Electrically short monopoles are widely used since they are more compact, and at long wavelengths construction limitations make it impractical to build an antenna mast a quarter wavelength high.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Even a very short rod a small fraction of a wavelength long can be impedance matched to a transmitter so it absorbs all the power from the feedline.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] However as the length is decreased the antenna eventually becomes inefficient due to its low radiation resistance.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The radiation resistance is only part of the feedpoint resistance at the antenna terminals.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The power $P_{\text{IN}}$ fed to the antenna is split proportionally between these two resistances.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The power $P_{\text{R}}$ consumed by radiation resistance is converted to radio waves, the desired function of the antenna, while the power $P_{\text{L}}$ consumed by loss resistance is converted to heat, representing a waste of transmitter power.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] So for minimum power loss it is desirable that the radiation resistance be much greater than the loss resistance.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] As the monopole is made shorter it's radiation resistance decreases and a greater proportion of the transmitter power is dissipated in the loss resistance.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] In the VLF band the huge top-loaded wire monopoles used by megawatt military transmitters are often less than 0.01 wavelengths high and have radiation resistance of less than 0.1 ohm.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Even with extremely low resistance ground systems they are often only 15% to 30% efficient.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Another disadvantage of electrically short monopoles is that as the antenna is made shorter and the radiation resistance decreases, the capacitance decreases and so the capacitive reactance increases.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The low resistance in combination with the capacitance of the antenna and inductance of the required loading coil gives the antenna a large Q factor; this means it has a narrow bandwidth, which reduces the data rate that can be transmitted or received.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Antennas in the VLF band often have a bandwidth of only 50 to 100 hertz.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The Chu-Harrington limit gives the minimum Q factor for a small antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] To increase the radiated power of an electrically short monopole, capacitance to ground can be added to the top by attaching horizontal metal conductors, insulated from ground, to the top of the element.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] This results in increased current in the vertical monopole element, to charge and discharge the capacitance each cycle.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Since the power radiated by a monopole is proportional to the square of the current in the radiating element, this increases the radiated power and thus the radiation resistance.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The buried radial wire ground system under the antenna serves as the bottom plate of the 'capacitor'.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Mast radiators sometimes include a circular structure of radial rods at the top of the mast; this is called a 'top hat'.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] At lower frequencies in the LF and VLF bands larger top loads are used.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The T antenna consists of a vertical wire driven at the bottom, rising to attach to the center of a horizontal top load wire insulated at both ends, supported by masts.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] Multiple parallel top load wires can be used to increase capacitance.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The largest top loaded antenna is the umbrella antenna, consisting of a monopole mast radiator with many diagonal top load wires radiating symmetrically from the top, anchored to the ground through insulators.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] To tune out the high capacitive reactance and make the antenna resonant a large loading coil is required in series with the feedline at the base of the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] At low frequencies, due to the high capacitance and low radiation resistance, the top loaded monopole has a very narrow bandwidth.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] This may limit the width of sidebands and thus the data rate that can be transmitted.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] High power transmitting antennas in the VLF band typically have Q of several hundred and bandwidths less than 100 Hz.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The energy stored in the antenna, stored alternately as an electrostatic field in the top load and a magnetic field in the loading coil, is hundreds of times the energy input from the transmitter each cycle.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The voltage at the ends of the top-load wires is very high, Q times the feed voltage, and may be hundreds of kilovolts, requiring very good insulation.
[src:antenna-theory/monopole-antenna-p02] The antenna must be tuned to resonance with the transmitter using a variometer coil.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] An antenna **radiation pattern** (or **antenna pattern** or **far-field pattern**) is the *directional* (angular) dependence of the field strength (sometimes also the phase) of the radio waves from the antenna or other source.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Particularly in the fields of fiber optics, lasers, and integrated optics, the term radiation pattern may also be used as a synonym for the **near-field pattern** or **Fresnel pattern**.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] This refers to the *positional* dependence of the electromagnetic field in the near field, or Fresnel region of the source.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The near-field pattern is most commonly defined over a plane placed in front of the source, or over a cylindrical or spherical surface enclosing it.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The far-field pattern of an antenna may be determined experimentally at an antenna range, or alternatively, the near-field pattern may be found using a *near-field scanner*, and the radiation pattern deduced from it by computation.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The far-field radiation pattern can also be calculated from the antenna shape by computer programs such as NEC.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Other software, like HFSS can also compute the near field.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Very often, only the relative amplitude is plotted, normalized either to the amplitude on the antenna boresight, or to the total radiated power.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The plotted quantity may be shown on a linear scale, or in dB.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The plot is typically represented as a three-dimensional graph (as at right), or as separate graphs in the vertical plane and horizontal plane.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] This is often known as a **polar diagram**.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] It is a fundamental property of antennas that the **receiving pattern** (sensitivity as a function of direction) of an antenna when used for receiving is identical to the far-field radiation pattern of the antenna when used for transmitting.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] This is a consequence of the reciprocity theorem of electromagnetics and is proved below.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Therefore, in discussions of radiation patterns the antenna can be viewed as either transmitting or receiving, whichever is more convenient.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] There are limits to reciprocity: It applies only to *passive* antenna elements – *active* antennas that incorporate amplifiers or other individually powered components are *not* reciprocal.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] And even when the antenna is made of exclusively of passive elements, reciprocity only applies to the waves emitted and intercepted by the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Since electromagnetic radiation is dipole radiation, it is not possible to build an antenna that radiates coherently equally in all directions, although such a hypothetical isotropic antenna is used as a reference to calculate antenna gain.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The simplest antennas, monopole and dipole antennas, consist of one or two straight metal rods along a common axis.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] These axially symmetric antennas have radiation patterns with a similar symmetry, called omnidirectional patterns; they radiate equal power in all directions perpendicular to the antenna, with the power varying only with the angle to the axis, dropping off to zero on the antenna's axis.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] This illustrates the general principle that if the shape of an antenna is symmetrical, its radiation pattern will have the same symmetry.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] In most antennas, the radiation from the different parts of the antenna interferes at some angles; the radiation pattern of the antenna can be considered an interference pattern.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] This results in minimum or zero radiation at certain angles where the radio waves from the different parts arrive out of phase, and local maxima of radiation at other angles where the radio waves arrive in phase.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Therefore, the radiation plot of most antennas shows a pattern of maxima called "*lobes*" at various angles, separated by "*nulls*" at which the radiation goes to zero.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The larger the antenna is compared to a wavelength, the more lobes there will be.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] In a directional antenna in which the objective is to emit the radio waves in one particular direction, the antenna is designed to radiate most of its power in the lobe directed in the desired direction.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Therefore, in the radiation plot this lobe appears larger than the others; it is called the "*main lobe*".
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The axis of maximum radiation, passing through the center of the main lobe, is called the "*beam axis*" or *boresight axis*".
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] In some antennas, such as split-beam antennas, there may exist more than one major lobe.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The other lobes beside the main lobe, representing unwanted radiation in other directions, are called minor lobes.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The minor lobes oriented at an angle to the main lobe are called "*side lobes*".
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The minor lobe in the opposite direction (180°) from the main lobe is called the "*back lobe*".
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Minor lobes usually represent radiation in undesired directions, so in directional antennas a design goal is usually to reduce the minor lobes.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Side lobes are normally the largest of the minor lobes.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The level of minor lobes is usually expressed as a ratio of the power density in the lobe in question to that of the major lobe.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] This ratio is often termed the side lobe ratio or side lobe level.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Side lobe levels of −20 dB or greater are usually not desirable in many applications.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Attainment of a side lobe level smaller than −30 dB usually requires very careful design and construction.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] In most radar systems, for example, low side lobe ratios are very important to minimize false target indications through the side lobes.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] For a complete proof, see the reciprocity (electromagnetism) article.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Here, we present a common simple proof limited to the approximation of two antennas separated by a large distance compared to the size of the antenna, in a homogeneous medium.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The first antenna is the test antenna whose patterns are to be investigated; this antenna is free to point in any direction.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The second antenna is a reference antenna, which points rigidly at the first antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Each antenna is alternately connected to a transmitter having a particular source impedance, and a receiver having the same input impedance (the impedance may differ between the two antennas).
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] It is assumed that the two antennas are sufficiently far apart that the properties of the transmitting antenna are not affected by the load placed upon it by the receiving antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Consequently, the amount of power transferred from the transmitter to the receiver can be expressed as the product of two independent factors; one depending on the directional properties of the transmitting antenna, and the other depending on the directional properties of the receiving antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Here, the angles $\theta$ and $\Phi$ indicate a dependence on direction from the antenna, and $P_{t}$ stands for the power the transmitter would deliver into a matched load.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The gain G may be broken down into three factors; the antenna gain (the directional redistribution of the power), the radiation efficiency (accounting for ohmic losses in the antenna), and lastly the loss due to mismatch between the antenna and transmitter.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Strictly, to include the mismatch, it should be called the **realized gain**, but this is not common usage.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Here W is the power density of the incident radiation, and A is the antenna aperture or effective area of the antenna (the area the antenna would need to occupy in order to intercept the observed captured power).
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The directional arguments are now relative to the receiving antenna, and again A is taken to include ohmic and mismatch losses.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] where G and A are directionally dependent properties of the transmitting and receiving antennas respectively.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Here, the gain $G_{2}$ and effective area $A_{2}$ of antenna 2 are fixed, because the orientation of this antenna is fixed with respect to the first.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Now for a given disposition of the antennas, the reciprocity theorem requires that the power transfer is equally effective in each direction, i.e.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] i.e. the directional dependence of the (receiving) effective aperture and the (transmitting) gain are identical (QED).
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Furthermore, the constant of proportionality is the same irrespective of the nature of the antenna, and so must be the same for all antennas.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Analysis of a particular antenna (such as a Hertzian dipole), shows that this constant is ${\frac {\lambda ^{2}}{4\pi }}$ , where $\lambda$ is the free-space wavelength.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] Even for a receiving antenna, it is more usual to state the gain than to specify the effective aperture.
[src:antenna-theory/radiation-pattern] The effective aperture is however of interest for comparison with the actual physical size of the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] A **Yagi–Uda antenna**, or **Yagi antenna**, is a directional antenna consisting of two or more parallel resonant antenna elements in an end-fire array; these elements are most often metal rods (or discs) acting as half-wave dipoles.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Yagi–Uda antennas consist of a single driven element connected to a radio transmitter or receiver (or both) through a transmission line, and additional *passive radiators* with no electrical connection, usually including one so-called *reflector* and any number of *directors*.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] It was invented in 1926 by Shintaro Uda of Tohoku Imperial University, Japan, with a lesser role played by his boss Hidetsugu Yagi.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Reflector elements (usually only one is used) are slightly longer than the driven dipole and placed behind the driven element, *opposite* the direction of intended transmission.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Directors, on the other hand, are a little shorter and placed in front of the driven element *in* the intended direction.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] These parasitic elements are typically off-tuned short-circuited dipole elements, that is, instead of a break at the feedpoint (like the driven element) a solid rod is used.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] They receive and reradiate the radio waves from the driven element but in a different phase determined by their exact lengths.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Their effect is to modify the driven element's radiation pattern.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The waves from the multiple elements superpose and interfere to enhance radiation in a single direction, increasing the antenna's gain in that direction.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Also called a beam antenna and parasitic array, the Yagi is widely used as a directional antenna on the HF, VHF and UHF bands.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] It has moderate to high gain of up to 20 dBi, depending on the number of elements used, and a front-to-back ratio of up to 20 dB.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] It radiates linearly polarized radio waves and is usually mounted for either horizontal or vertical polarization.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] It is relatively lightweight, inexpensive and simple to construct.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The bandwidth of a Yagi antenna, the frequency range over which it maintains its gain and feedpoint impedance, is narrow, just a few percent of the center frequency, decreasing for models with higher gain, making it ideal for fixed-frequency applications.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The largest and best-known use is as rooftop terrestrial television antennas, but it is also used for point-to-point fixed communication links, radar, and long-distance shortwave communication by broadcasting stations and radio amateurs.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The antenna was invented by Shintaro Uda of Tohoku Imperial University, Japan, in 1926, with a lesser role played by Hidetsugu Yagi.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] However, the name *Yagi* has become more familiar, while the name of Uda, who applied the idea in practice or established the conception through experiment, is often omitted.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] This appears to have been due to the fact that Yagi based his work on Uda's pre-announcement and developed the principle of the absorption phenomenon Yagi had announced earlier.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Yagi filed a patent application in Japan on the new idea, without Uda's name in it, and later transferred the patent to the Marconi Company in the UK.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Incidentally, in the US, the patent was transferred to RCA Corporation.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Yagi antennas were first widely used during World War II in radar systems by Japan, Germany, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] After the war, they saw extensive development as home television antennas.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The Yagi–Uda antenna typically consists of a number of parallel thin rod elements, each approximately a half wave in length.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Rarely, the elements are discs rather than rods.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Often they are supported on a perpendicular crossbar or "boom" along their centers.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Usually there is a single dipole driven element consisting of two collinear rods each connected to one side of the transmission line, and a variable number of parasitic elements, *reflectors* on one side and optionally one or more *directors* on the other side.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The parasitic elements are not electrically connected to the transmission line and serve as passive radiators, reradiating the radio waves to modify the radiation pattern.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Typical spacings between elements vary from about 1⁄10 to 1⁄4 of a wavelength, depending on the specific design.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The directors are slightly shorter than the driven element, while the reflector(s) are slightly longer.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The radiation pattern is unidirectional, with the main lobe along the axis perpendicular to the elements in the plane of the elements, off the end with the directors.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Conveniently, the dipole parasitic elements have a node (point of zero RF voltage) at their centre, so they can be attached to a conductive metal support at that point without need of insulation, without disturbing their electrical operation.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] They are usually bolted or welded to the antenna's central support boom.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The most common form of the driven element is one fed at its centre so its two halves must be insulated where the boom supports them.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The gain increases with the number of parasitic elements used.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Only one reflector is normally used since the improvement of gain with additional reflectors is small, but more reflectors may be employed for other reasons such as wider bandwidth.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Yagis have been built with 40 directors and more.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The bandwidth of an antenna is, by one definition, the width of the band of frequencies having a gain within 3 dB (one-half the power) of its maximum gain.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The Yagi–Uda array in its basic form has a narrow bandwidth, 2–3 percent of the centre frequency.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] There is a tradeoff between gain and bandwidth, with the bandwidth narrowing as more elements are used.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] For applications that require wider bandwidths, such as terrestrial television, Yagi–Uda antennas commonly feature trigonal reflectors, and larger diameter conductors, in order to cover the relevant portions of the VHF and UHF bands.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Wider bandwidth can also be achieved by the use of "traps", as described below.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Yagi–Uda antennas used for amateur radio are sometimes designed to operate on multiple bands.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] These elaborate designs create electrical breaks along each element (both sides) at which point a parallel LC (inductor and capacitor) circuit is inserted.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] This so-called *trap* has the effect of truncating the element at the higher frequency band, making it approximately a half wavelength in length.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] At the lower frequency, the entire element (including the remaining inductance due to the trap) is close to half-wave resonance, implementing a *different* Yagi–Uda antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Using a second set of traps, a "triband" antenna can be resonant at three different bands.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Given the associated costs of erecting an antenna and rotator system above a tower, the combination of antennas for three amateur bands in one unit is a practical solution.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The use of traps is not without disadvantages, however, as they reduce the bandwidth of the antenna on the individual bands and reduce the antenna's electrical efficiency and subject the antenna to additional mechanical considerations (wind loading, water and insect ingress).
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Consider a Yagi–Uda consisting of a reflector, driven element, and a single director as shown here.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The driven element is typically a 1⁄2*λ* dipole or folded dipole and is the only member of the structure that is directly excited (electrically connected to the feedline).
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] All the other elements are considered *parasitic*.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] That is, they reradiate power which they receive from the driven element.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] They also interact with each other, but this mutual coupling is neglected in the following simplified explanation, which applies to far-field conditions.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] One way of thinking about the operation of such an antenna is to consider a parasitic element to be a normal dipole element of finite diameter fed at its centre, with a short circuit across its feed point.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The principal part of the current in a loaded receiving antenna is distributed as in a center-driven antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] It is proportional to the effective length of the antenna and is in phase with the incident electric field if the passive dipole is excited exactly at its resonance frequency.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Now we imagine the current as the source of a power wave at the (short-circuited) port of the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] As is well known in transmission line theory, a short circuit reflects the incident voltage 180 degrees out of phase.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] So one could as well model the operation of the parasitic element as the superposition of a dipole element receiving power and sending it down a transmission line to a matched load, and a transmitter sending the same amount of power up the transmission line back toward the antenna element.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] If the transmitted voltage wave were 180 degrees out of phase with the received wave at that point, the superposition of the two voltage waves would give zero voltage, equivalent to shorting out the dipole at the feedpoint (making it a solid element, as it is).
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] However, the current of the backward wave is in phase with the current of the incident wave.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] This current drives the reradiation of the (passive) dipole element.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] At some distance, the reradiated electric field is described by the far-field component of the radiation field of a dipole antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Its phase includes the propagation delay (relating to the current) and an additional 90 degrees lagging phase offset.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Thus, the reradiated field may be thought as having a 90 degrees lagging phase with respect to the incident field.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Parasitic elements involved in Yagi–Uda antennas are not exactly resonant but are somewhat shorter (or longer) than 1⁄2*λ* so that the phase of the element's current is modified with respect to its excitation from the driven element.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The so-called *reflector* element, being longer than 1⁄2*λ*, has an inductive reactance, which means the phase of its current lags the phase of the open-circuit voltage that would be induced by the received field.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The *director* element, on the other hand, being shorter than 1⁄2*λ*, has a capacitive reactance with the voltage phase lagging that of the current.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The phase delay is thus smaller than 90 degrees and, if the director element is made sufficiently short, the phase delay may be imagined to approach zero and the incident wave and the wave reemitted by the reflector interfere constructively in the forward direction.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Interference also occurs in the backward direction.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] To illustrate the effect, we assume zero and 180 degrees phase delay for the reemission of director and reflector, respectively, and assume a distance of a quarter wavelength between the driven and the passive element.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Under these conditions the wave reemitted by the director interferes destructively with the wave emitted by the driven element in the backward direction (away from the passive element), and the wave reemitted by the reflector interferes constructively.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] In reality, the phase delay of passive dipole elements does not reach the extreme values of zero and 180 degrees.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Thus, the elements are given the correct lengths and spacings so that the radio waves radiated by the driven element and those re-radiated by the parasitic elements all arrive at the front of the antenna in-phase, so they superpose and add, increasing signal strength in the forward direction.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] In other words, the crest of the forward wave from the reflector element reaches the driven element just as the crest of the wave is emitted from that element.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] These waves reach the first director element just as the crest of the wave is emitted from that element, and so on.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The waves in the reverse direction interfere destructively, cancelling out, so the signal strength radiated in the reverse direction is small.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Thus the antenna radiates a unidirectional beam of radio waves from the front (director end) of the antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] While the above qualitative explanation is useful for understanding how parasitic elements can enhance the driven elements' radiation in one direction at the expense of the other, the assumption of an additional 90 degrees (leading or lagging) phase shift of the reemitted wave is not valid.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Typically, the phase shift in the passive element is much smaller.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Moreover, to increase the effect of the passive radiators, they should be placed close to the driven element, so that they can collect and reemit a significant part of the primary radiation.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] A more realistic model of a Yagi–Uda array using just a driven element and a director is illustrated in the accompanying diagram.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The wave generated by the driven element (green) propagates in both the forward and reverse directions (as well as other directions, not shown).
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The director receives that wave slightly delayed in time (amounting to a phase delay of about 45° which will be important for the reverse direction calculations later).
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Due to the director's shorter length, the current generated in the director is advanced in phase (by about 20°) with respect to the incident field and emits an electromagnetic field, which lags (under far-field conditions) this current by 90°.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The net effect is a wave emitted by the director (blue) which is about 70° (20° - 90°) retarded with respect to that from the driven element (green), in this particular design.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] These waves combine to produce the net forward wave (bottom, right) with an amplitude somewhat larger than the individual waves.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] In the reverse direction, on the other hand, the additional delay of the wave from the director (blue) due to the spacing between the two elements (about 45° of phase delay traversed twice) causes it to be about 160° (70° + 2 × 45°) out of phase with the wave from the driven element (green).
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The net effect of these two waves, when added (bottom, left), is partial cancellation.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The combination of the director's position and shorter length has thus obtained a unidirectional rather than the bidirectional response of the driven (half-wave dipole) element alone.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] When a passive radiator is placed close (less than a quarter wavelength distance) to the driven dipole, it interacts with the near field, in which the phase-to-distance relation is not governed by propagation delay, as would be the case in the far field.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Thus, the amplitude and phase relation between the driven and the passive element cannot be understood with a model of successive collection and reemission of a wave that has become completely disconnected from the primary radiating element.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Instead, the two antenna elements form a coupled system, in which, for example, the self-impedance (or radiation resistance) of the driven element is strongly influenced by the passive element.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] A full analysis of such a system requires computing the *mutual impedances* between the dipole elements which implicitly takes into account the propagation delay due to the finite spacing between elements and near-field coupling effects.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] We model element number *j* as having a feedpoint at the centre with a voltage *V*j and a current *I*j flowing into it.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The solution of the system then is as follows.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Let the driven element be designated 1 so that *V*1 and *I*1 are the voltage and current supplied by the transmitter.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The parasitic element is designated 2, and since it is shorted at its "feedpoint" we can write that *V*2 = 0.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] This is the current induced in the parasitic element due to the current *I*1 in the driven element.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] where we have substituted *Z*12 = *Z*21.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] With only the driven element present the driving point impedance would have simply been *Z*11, but has now been modified by the presence of the parasitic element.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] And now knowing the phase (and amplitude) of *I*2 in relation to *I*1 as computed above allows us to determine the radiation pattern (gain as a function of direction) due to the currents flowing in these two elements.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Solution of such an antenna with more than two elements proceeds along the same lines, setting each *V*j = 0 for all but the driven element, and solving for the currents in each element (and the voltage *V*1 at the feedpoint).
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Generally the mutual coupling tends to lower the impedance of the primary radiator and thus, folded dipole antennas are frequently used because of their large radiation resistance, which is reduced to the typical 50 to 75 Ohm range by coupling with the passive elements.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] However using the above kinds of iterative analysis, one can calculate the performance of a given a set of parameters and adjust them to optimize the gain (perhaps subject to some constraints).
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Since with an *n* element Yagi–Uda antenna, there are 2*n* − *1* parameters to adjust (the element lengths and relative spacings), this iterative analysis method is not straightforward.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The mutual impedances plotted above only apply to *λ*/2 length elements, so these might need to be recomputed to get good accuracy.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The current distribution along a real antenna element is only approximately given by the usual assumption of a classical standing wave, requiring a solution of Hallen's integral equation taking into account the other conductors.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Such a complete exact analysis, considering all of the interactions mentioned, is rather overwhelming, and approximations are inevitable on the path to finding a usable antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Consequently, these antennas are often empirical designs using an element of trial and error, often starting with an existing design modified according to one's hunch.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The result might be checked by direct measurement or by computer simulation.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] By adjusting the distance between the adjacent directors it is possible to reduce the back lobe of the radiation pattern.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The Yagi–Uda antenna was invented in 1926 by Shintaro Uda of Tohoku Imperial University, Sendai, Japan, with the guidance of Hidetsugu Yagi, also of Tohoku Imperial University.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Yagi and Uda published their first report on the wave projector directional antenna.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Yagi demonstrated a proof of concept, but the engineering problems proved to be more onerous than conventional systems.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Yagi published the first English-language reference on the antenna in a 1928 survey article on short wave research in Japan and it came to be associated with his name.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The Yagi was first widely used during World War II for airborne radar sets, because of its simplicity and directionality.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Despite its being invented in Japan, many Japanese radar engineers were unaware of the design until late in the war, partly due to rivalry between the Army and Navy.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The Japanese military authorities first became aware of this technology after the Battle of Singapore when they captured the notes of a British radar technician that mentioned "yagi antenna".
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Japanese intelligence officers did not even recognise that Yagi was a Japanese name in this context.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] When questioned, the technician said it was an antenna named after a Japanese professor.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] A horizontally polarized array can be seen on many different types of WWII aircraft, particularly those types engaged in maritime patrol, or night fighters, commonly installed on the lower surface of each wing.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Two types that often carried such equipment are the Grumman TBF Avenger carrier-based US Navy aircraft and the Consolidated PBY Catalina long range patrol seaplane.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Vertically polarized arrays can be seen on the cheeks of the P-61 and on the nose cones of many WWII aircraft, notably the Lichtenstein radar-equipped examples of the German Junkers Ju 88R-1 fighter-bomber, and the British Bristol Beaufighter night-fighter and Short Sunderland flying-boat.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Indeed, the latter had so many antenna elements arranged on its back – in addition to its formidable turreted defensive armament in the nose and tail, and atop the hull – it was nicknamed the *fliegendes Stachelschwein*, or "Flying Porcupine" by German airmen.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] After World War II, the advent of television broadcasting motivated extensive adaptation of the Yagi–Uda design for rooftop television reception in the VHF band (and later for UHF television) and also as an FM radio antenna in fringe areas.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] A major drawback was the Yagi's inherently narrow bandwidth, eventually solved by the adoption of the wideband log-periodic dipole array (LPDA).
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] Yet the Yagi's higher gain compared to the LPDA makes it the best for fringe reception, and complicated Yagi designs and combination with other antenna technologies have been developed to permit its operation over the broad television bands.
[src:antenna-theory/yagi-uda-antenna] The Yagi–Uda antenna was named an IEEE Milestone in 1995.
